NCIt Definition: Problem associated with software, firmware, and/or hardware elements that control the execution of computer programs and provides such services as computer resource allocation, job control, input/output control, and file management in a computer system.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with software, firmware, and/or hardware elements that control the execution of computer programs and provides such services as computer resource allocation, job control, input/output control, and file management in a computer system.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with malfunction of the computer operating system as opposed to an application software problem.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with malfunction of the computer operating system as opposed to an application software problem.

NCIt Preferred Term: Operating System Version or Upgrade Problem
NCIt Definition: Problem associated with replacing an older operating system to an up-to-date operating system.
CDRH Preferred Term: Operating System Version or Upgrade Problem
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with replacing an older operating system to an up-to-date operating system.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with unauthorized access to or modification of a software system resulting in a loss of confidentiality, integrity, or availability of written program code, application software, or data or entire device.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with unauthorized access to or modification of a software system resulting in a loss of confidentiality, integrity, or availability of written program code, application software, or data or entire device.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the acquisition of computer programming codes that can replicate and spread from one computer system to another thereby leading to damaged software, hardware and data.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the acquisition of computer programming codes that can replicate and spread from one computer system to another thereby leading to damaged software, hardware and data.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with an access that was not permitted to the computer system that may lead to modification of program, corruption of data, or and break in network security. This concept is closely associated with computer integrity which is the degree to which a system or component prevents unauthorized access to, or modification of, computer programs or data.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with an access that was not permitted to the computer system that may lead to modification of program, corruption of data, or and break in network security. This concept is closely associated with computer integrity which is the degree to which a system or component prevents unauthorized access to, or modification of, computer programs or data.

NCIt Definition: Problems relating to a system, component, file, procedure, or person available to replace or help restore a primary item in the event of a failure or externally caused disaster.
CDRH Definition: Problems relating to a system, component, file, procedure, or person available to replace or help restore a primary item in the event of a failure or externally caused disaster.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the inability to backup or to retrieve a backed up version (corrupted file) of device data or system files.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the inability to backup or to retrieve a backed up version (corrupted file) of device data or system files.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with a failure to transition from a primary system, component, file, procedure to a backup in response to a failure in the primary item.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with a failure to transition from a primary system, component, file, procedure to a backup in response to a failure in the primary item.

NCIt Definition: Event in which data (charting, orders, results) is not correctly stored, transferred, updated, or displayed.
CDRH Definition: Event in which data (charting, orders, results) is not correctly stored, transferred, updated, or displayed.

NCIt Definition: Event in which data is unintentionally permanently or temporarily lost, deleted, corrupted, or overwritten.
CDRH Definition: Event in which data is unintentionally permanently or temporarily lost, deleted, corrupted, or overwritten.

NCIt Definition: Event in which data is accessed by the healthcare provider and either the wrong patient or the wrong data is retrieved despite correct inquiry procedures.
CDRH Definition: Event in which data is accessed by the healthcare provider and either the wrong patient or the wrong data is retrieved despite correct inquiry procedures.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with programming of calendar dates and/or time as a factor in the operation of the device.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with programming of calendar dates and/or time as a factor in the operation of the device.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with linking of a device and/or the functional units set up to provide means for a transfer of liquid, gas, electricity or data.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with linking of the device and/or the functional units set up to provide means for a transfer of liquid, gas, electricity or data.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with linking of a device whereby their functional units set up to provide means for a transfer of fluid, gas, or data is prevented or impeded.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with linking of the device whereby their functional units set up to provide means for a transfer of fluid, gas, or data is prevented or impeded.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the device being unassociated in such a way that fluid, gas, power or signal information may not be transferred from one device to another.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the device being unassociated in such a way that fluid, gas, power or signal information may not be transferred from one to another.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the linking of the device having a sufficient open space to prevent gas, liquid or electrical current flow between connectors.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the linking of the device having a sufficient open space to prevent gas, liquid or electrical current flow between connectors.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the linking of the device whereby termination of the transfer of liquid, gas, electricity, or information cannot be accomplished, or linking components do not come apart, or disconnect, when expected.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the linking of the device whereby termination of the transfer of liquid, gas, electricity, or information cannot be accomplished, or linking components do not come apart, or disconnect, when expected.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the connection of the device being loose or intermittent.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the connection of the device being loose or intermittent.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the connection of the device being improper or not in accordance with device specification, requirements or intended uses.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the connection of the device being improper or not in accordance with device specification, requirements or intended uses.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with a partial linking of the device whereby the device may appear to be connected however only a partial, intermittent or no transfer of liquid, gas, electricity, or information can be accomplished.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with a partial linking of the device whereby device may appear to be connected however only a partial, intermittent or no transfer of liquid, gas, electricity, or information can be accomplished.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the connection of the device whereby channels, switching systems, and other functional units set up to provide means for a transfer of liquid, gas, electricity, or information do not match or fit.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the connection of the device whereby channels, switching systems, and other functional units set up to provide means for a transfer of liquid, gas, electricity, or information do not match or fit.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with a device sending or receiving signals or data. This includes transmission among internal components of the device to which the device is intended to communicate.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the device sending or receiving signals or data. This includes transmission among internal components of the device to which the device is intended to communicate.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with a failure of the device to read a signal for interpretation or measurement.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with a failure of the device to read a signal for interpretation or measurement.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with a failure of the device to transmit a record for interpretation or measurement.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with a failure of the device to transmit a record for interpretation or measurement.

NCIt Definition: Inconsistent or lack of intended communication of data among internal components or with other external devices.
CDRH Definition: Inconsistent or lack of intended communication of data among internal components or with other external devices.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with variability of the transmission of telemetry signals.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with variability of the transmission of telemetry signals.

NCIt Definition: Problems with the RF wireless technology characteristics and performance (e.g., frequency, output power, range, reception), wireless quality of service, wireless coexistence, security of wireless signals and data, and electromagnetic compatibility.
CDRH Definition: Problems with the RF wireless technology characteristics and performance (e.g., frequency, output power, range, reception), wireless quality of service, wireless coexistence, security of wireless signals and data, and electromagnetic compatibility.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the device failing to deliver or draw liquids or gases as intended (e.g. delivering drugs at incorrect rate, problems with drawing fluid from a system). This includes vacuum collection devices and manual or mechanical pumps.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the device failing to deliver or draw liquids or gases as intended (e.g. delivering drugs at incorrect rate, problems with drawing fluid from a system). This includes vacuum collection devices and manual or mechanical pumps.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the inability of the device to release its contents.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the deflation of the device including unintended deflation or inadequate deflation.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the inability to deflate a device which is intended to deflate.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the inability to deflate a device which is intended to deflate.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the unintended deflation of a device which was not designed to deflate or not at that point in time or not to that extent.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the unintended deflation of a device which was not designed to deflate or not at that point in time or not to that extent.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with a delivery overdose of therapeutic agents, such as drugs or fluids being delivered into a device or a patient.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with a delivery overdose of therapeutic agents, such as drugs or fluids being delivered into a device or a patient.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the method or amount of time associated with the delivery of a fluid. Time to delivery or amount of delivered entity may be affected.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the method or amount of time associated with the delivery of a fluid. Time to delivery or amount of delivered entity may be affected.

NCIt Definition: Complete failure to fill as part of an automated process. For insufficient filling use Short Fill. For excessive filling use Overfill. For inconsistent filling use Volume Accuracy Problem.
CDRH Definition: Complete failure to fill as part of an automated process. For insufficient filling use "Short Fill". For excessive filling use "Overfill". For inconsistent filling use "Volume Accuracy Problem".

NCIt Definition: Excessive filling of a device. For complete failure to fill use inability to auto-fill. For insufficient filling use Short Fill. For inconsistent filling - use Volume Accuracy Problem.
CDRH Definition: Excessive filling of a device. For complete failure to fill use "inability to auto-fill". For insufficient filling use "Short Fill". For inconsistent filling use "Volume Accuracy Problem".

NCIt Definition: Insufficient filling of a device. For complete failure to fill use inability to auto-fill. For insufficient filling use short fill. For inconsistent filling - use Volume Accuracy Problem.
CDRH Definition: Insufficient filling of a device. For complete failure to fill use "inability to auto-fill". For insufficient filling use "short fill". For inconsistent filling use "Volume Accuracy Problem".

NCIt Definition: Inconsistent filling of a device. This describes a problem which is observed to vary between overfilling and under filling, and may be intermittent. Use Overfill or Short Fill if problem is consistent.
CDRH Definition: Inconsistent filling of a device. This describes a problem which is observed to vary between overfilling and under filling, and may be intermittent. Use "Overfill" or "Short Fill" if problem is consistent.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the process of passing a substance through a porous medium, e.g., a blood clot filter for the removal of suspended matter.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the process of passing a substance through a porous medium, e.g., a blood clot filter for the removal of suspended matter.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the filter failing to remove items or substances which should have been removed.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the filter failing to remove items or substances which should have been removed.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the transfer of fluid between the blood and dialysate through the dialysis membrane due to a pressure gradient (trans-membrane pressure) existing between the blood and dialysate compartments.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the transfer of fluid between the blood and dialysate through the dialysis membrane due to a pressure gradient (trans-membrane pressure) existing between the blood and dialysate compartments.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the regulation and delivery of therapeutic agents (e.g. air, gas, drugs or fluids into a device or a patient under positive pressure).
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the regulation and delivery of therapeutic agents (e.g. air, gas, drugs or fluids into a device or a patient under positive pressure).

NCIt Definition: Continuous flow of fluid (e.g. liquid, gas) against the intended flow direction.
CDRH Definition: Continuous flow of fluid (e.g. liquid, gas) against the intended flow direction.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with uncontrolled flow of infusion of air, gas or fluids.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with uncontrolled flow of infusion of air, gas or fluids.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the increased rate of change in temperature, pressure, or other variables as a function of distance, time, etc.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the increased rate of change in temperature, pressure, or other variables as a function of distance, time, etc.

NCIt Definition: Delivery at endpoint not as intended; either too low or too high.
CDRH Definition: Delivery at endpoint not as intended; either too low or too high.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with fluctuations in the flow volume delivered per time, even if end volume is correct, and delivered in the correct total time.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with fluctuations in the flow volume delivered per time, even if end volume is correct, and delivered in the correct total time.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the infusion not being steady, characterized by intermittent stoppages to the flow.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the infusion not being stead- characterised by intermittent stoppages to the flow.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with partial backflow, compromising the device's flow output.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with partial backflow, compromising the device's flow output.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with flow rate. Flow volume delivered over time is not reaching intended flow rate.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with flow rate. Flow volume delivered over time is not reaching intended flow rate.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the amount of gas that is inspired and expired during one respiratory cycle.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the amount of gas that is inspired and expired during one respiratory cycle.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the inability of the device to expand or enlarge with the intended inflation agent (e.g. saline or air).
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the inability of the device to expand or enlarge with the intended inflation agent (e.g. saline or air).

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with an insufficient dose of therapeutic agents, e.g., drugs or fluids being delivered into a patient under positive pressure.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with an insufficient dose of therapeutic agents, e.g., drugs or fluids being delivered into a patient under positive pressure.

NCIt Definition: Problem arising from the device failing to deliver the specified liquid or gas.
CDRH Definition: Problem arising from the device failing to deliver the specified liquid or gas.

NCIt Definition: Failure (=complete nonperformance) with regard to the intended function of delivery.
CDRH Definition: Failure (=complete nonperformance) with regard to the intended function of delivery.

NCIt Definition: Failure (=complete nonperformance) with regard to the intended function of infusion.
CDRH Definition: Failure (=complete nonperformance) with regard to the intended function of infusion.

NCIt Definition: Failure (=complete nonperformance) with regard to the intended function of irrigation.
CDRH Definition: Failure (=complete nonperformance) with regard to the intended function of irrigation.

NCIt Definition: Problem related to an obstruction or blockage within the device component (e.g. tube, opening, pipe) that results in restriction of flow.
CDRH Definition: Problem related to an obstruction or blockage within the device component (e.g. tube, opening, pipe) that results in restriction of flow (including blood clotting).

NCIt Definition: Problem related to an obstruction or blockage within the device component (e.g. tube, opening, pipe) that results in no flow.
CDRH Definition: Problem related to an obstruction or blockage within the device component (e.g. tube, opening, pipe) that results in no flow.

NCIt Definition: Problem related to an obstruction or blockage within the device component (e.g. tube, opening, pipe) that results in a reduction of the flow rate.
CDRH Definition: Problem related to an obstruction or blockage within the device component (e.g. tube, opening, pipe) that results in a reduction of the flow rate.

NCIt Definition: The device that is difficult to flush, possibly indicating an obstruction within device.
CDRH Definition: The device is difficult to flush, possibly indicating an obstruction within device.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the application of a force either internal or external to device that compromises the flow of fluid or gas.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the application of a force either internal or external to device that compromises the flow of fluid or gas.

NCIt Definition: Unintended decrease in pressure, compromising a medical device's intended function.
CDRH Definition: Unintended decrease in pressure, compromising the device's intended function.

NCIt Definition: Unintended increase in pressure, compromising the device's intended function.
CDRH Definition: Unintended increase in pressure, compromising the device's intended function.

NCIt Definition: Unintended complete loss of pressure, compromising the device's intended function.
CDRH Definition: Unintended complete loss of pressure, compromising the device's intended function.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with pump performance deviating from specifications in a way to compromise flow or infusion or dispensing.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with pump performance deviating from specifications in a way to compromise flow or infusion or dispensing.

NCIt Definition: Unintended decrease in pump speed and subsequent flow rate, compromising the intended function of a medical device.
CDRH Definition: Unintended decrease in pump speed and hence, probably, flow rate, compromising the intended function of the device.

NCIt Definition: Unintended increase in pump speed and hence, probably, flow rate, compromising the intended function of the device.
CDRH Definition: Unintended increase in pump speed and hence, probably, flow rate, compromising the intended function of the device.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the device which fails to start pumping.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the device which fails to start pumping.

NCIt Definition: Unexpected /unintended cessation of pump.
CDRH Definition: Unexpected/unintended cessation of pump.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with suction equipment, which may be a manual, electrical, vacuum or pressure source operated to evacuate and remove undesired substances (air, gas, fluid, or particulates) via tubing and collection bag.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with suction equipment, which may be a manual, electrical, vacuum or pressure source operated to evacuate and remove undesired substances (air, gas, fluid, or particulates) via tubing and collection bag.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the removal of fluid or gas from a body cavity due to decreased suction.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the removal of fluid or gas from a body cavity or device due to decreased suction.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the removal of excess fluid or gas from a body cavity due to increased suction.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the removal of fluid or gas from a body cavity or device due to increased suction.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the complete inability to provide suction.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the complete inability to provide suction.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the preparation of the device to begin pumping.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the preparation of the device to begin pumping.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the device failing to begin the priming process (i.e. the process of preparation of device for the delivery of fluids).
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the device failing to begin the priming process (i.e. the process of preparation of device for the delivery of fluids).

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with not adequately preparing the device.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with not adequately preparing the device.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with air in the device (e.g. air in line).
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with air in the device (e.g. air in line).

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with any deviations from the documented specifications of a medical device that relate to the sequence of events for activation, positioning or separation of device.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with any deviations from the documented specifications of the device that relate to the sequence of events for activation, positioning or separation of device. Note: Deployment is synonymous with activation.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the activation of a device.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the activation of the device. Note: Activation includes expansion.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the device failing to be activated including expansion.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the device failing to be activated including partial activation.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with delayed or difficult activation of the device.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with delayed or difficult activation of the device.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with early and unexpected activation of the device.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with early and unexpected activation of the device.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the unintended activation of the device, or a  device having been unexpectedly turned on during use.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the unintended activation of the device, or the device having been unexpectedly turned on during use.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with a device not responding to key or button inputs.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with a device not responding to key or button inputs.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the movement of the device to an intended location.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the movement of the device to an intended location.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the inability of the medical device to be positioned in a specified location.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the inability of the device to be positioned in a specified location.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the device being positioned in a location other than intended or specified.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the device being positioned in a location other than intended or specified.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with users experiencing difficulty or delay to position the device to a specified location.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with users experiencing difficulty or delay to position the device to a specified location.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with failure to move the device to an intended location.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with failure to move the device to an intended location.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with difficulty moving the device to an intended location (e.g. difficulty in advancing guide wire).
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with difficulty moving the device to an intended location (e.g. difficulty in advancing guide wire).

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with problems introducing or inserting the device, even if the user is operating the device in accordance with the instructions for use or labeling.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with problems introducing or inserting the device, even if the user is operating the device in accordance with the instructions for use or labeling.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the use of the device in terms of user experiencing difficulty to take out or get rid of the device, even if the user is operating device in accordance with the instructions for use or labeling.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the user experiencing difficulty when taking out the device, even if the user is operating device in accordance with the instructions for use or labeling.

NCIt Definition: Issue associated with the device and/or device accessories caught within patient vasculature, tissue, or other device.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the device caught within patient vasculature, tissue, or other device.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the detachment or separation of device.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the detachment or separation of the device.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the device or one of its components failing to detach or separate as intended.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the device or one of its components failing to detach or separate as intended.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with users experiencing difficulty or delay with detachment or separation of the device.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with users experiencing difficulty or delay with detachment or separation of the device.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with an early and unexpected detachment or separation of the device from the system.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with an early and unexpected detachment or separation of the device from the system.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with any deviations from the documented specifications of the device that relate to the implemented and inherited design features specific to devices used for reducing risks to patient or caregiver or maintaining risks within specified levels.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with any deviations from the documented specifications of the device that relate to the implemented and inherited design features specific to devices used for reducing risks to patient or caregiver or maintaining risks within specified levels.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the alarm system of the device.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the alarm system of the device.

NCIt Definition: A device does not display an alarm message when required.
CDRH Definition: The device does not display an alarm message when required.

NCIt Definition: The device fails to emit an audible alarm.
CDRH Definition: The device fails to emit an audible alarm.

NCIt Definition: The audible device alarm cannot be heard clearly.
CDRH Definition: The audible device alarm cannot be heard clearly.

NCIt Definition: A device alarm system operates with delay.
CDRH Definition: The device alarm system operates with delay.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the device providing incorrect alarm warning or alert to user.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the device providing incorrect alarm warning or alert to user.

NCIt Definition: The device alarm does not operate as expected and/or in agreement with device's specifications.
CDRH Definition: The device alarm does not operate as expected and/or in agreement with device's specifications.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the feature that prevents the unsafe use of the device.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the feature that prevents the unsafe use of the device.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the device fail-safe mechanism, which did not function or function in a non effective way, compromising safe use of the device.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the device fail-safe mechanism, which did not function or function in a non effective way, compromising safe use of the device.

NCIt Definition: The device that does not have a fail-safe mechanism, although such mechanism would be required for its appropriate and/or safe functioning.
CDRH Definition: The device does not have a fail-safe mechanism, although such mechanism would be required for its appropriate and/or safe functioning.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the device failing to perform an internal self-diagnostic process to ensure normal operation during or prior to use.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the device failing to perform an internal self-diagnostic process to ensure normal operation during or prior to use.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the inability of device to turn itself off when the device is not in an operable condition.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the inability of device to turn itself off when the device is not in an operable condition.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with setting a variable, register, or other storage location back to a prescribed state.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with setting a variable, register, or other storage location back to a prescribed state.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the device failing to set a variable, register, or other storage location back to a prescribed state.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the device failing to set a variable, register, or other storage location back to a prescribed state.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the device failing to set a variable, register, or other storage location back to zero.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the device failing to set a variable, register, or other storage location back to zero.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the device setting a variable, register, or other storage location to an inappropriate or unexpected state.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the device setting a variable, register, or other storage location to an inappropriate or unexpected state.

NCIt Definition: Problems with the activation of a protective measure indicator earlier than expected.
CDRH Definition: Problems with the activation of a protective measure indicator earlier than expected.

NCIt Definition: Problems with the early or unexpected activation of the elective replacement indicator.
CDRH Definition: Problems with the early or unexpected activation of the elective replacement indicator.

NCIt Definition: Problem with the early or unexpected activation of the end-of-life indicator.
CDRH Definition: Problem with the early or unexpected activation of the end-of-life indicator.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the device inability to act as a barrier for absorption of radiation energy in X-rays, gamma rays, etc.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the device inability to act as a barrier for absorption of radiation energy in X-rays, gamma rays, etc.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with compatibility between device, patients or substances (medication, body fluid, etc.).
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with compatibility between device, patients or substances (medication, body fluid, etc.)

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the incompatibility of any device while being operated in the same use environment thereby leading to a dysfunction between the devices.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the incompatibility of any device while being operated in the same use environment thereby leading to a dysfunction between the devices.

NCIt Definition: An accessory required for the intended purpose of the device appears incompatible with device, thus compromising the intended function of the device.
CDRH Definition: An accessory required for the intended purpose of the device appears incompatible with device, thus compromising the intended function of the device.

NCIt Definition: A component required for the proper functioning of a device is not compatible with other components or subassemblies of a device, thus compromising the intended function of a device.
CDRH Definition: A component required for the proper functioning of the device is not compatible with other components or subassemblies of the device, thus compromising the intended function of the device.

NCIt Definition: The inability of two or more devices to work together.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the incompatibility of two or more devices while being operated in the same use environment thereby leading to a dysfunction of more than one device.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the incompatibility of the measurement systems between and/or within device systems that are inherent to the individual device thereby leading to miscalculated or mismatched measurements from those devices, e.g., international metric system versus U.S. measurement system.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the incompatibility of the measurement systems between and/or within device systems that are inherent to the individual device thereby leading to miscalculated or mismatched measurements from those devices, e.g., international metric system versus U.S. measurement system.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the ability of two or more devices which are intended to be incompatible but are able to work or fit together.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the ability of two or more devices which are intended to be incompatible but are able to work or fit together.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the presence of any unexpected foreign substance found in a device, on its surface or in the package materials, which may affect performance or intended use of the device, or problem that compromise effective decontamination of the device.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the presence of any unexpected foreign substance found in the device, on its surface or in the package materials, which may affect performance or intended use of the device, or problem that compromise effective decontamination of the device.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the undesired introduction of impurities either chemical or microbiological in nature, or of foreign matter into or onto a device at the user facility.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the undesired introduction of impurities either chemical or microbiological in nature, or of foreign matter into or onto the device.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the undesired introduction of a biofilm coating into or onto the device.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the undesired introduction of a biofilm coating into or onto the device.

NCIt Preferred Term: Contamination of Device Ingredient or Reagent
NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the undesired introduction of impurities either chemical or microbiological in nature, or of foreign matter into or onto the device ingredient or reagent.
CDRH Preferred Term: Contamination of Device Ingredient or Reagent
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the undesired introduction of impurities either chemical or microbiological in nature, or of foreign matter into or onto the device ingredient or reagent.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the undesired presence of body fluid in/on the device, which are not part of the documented device specifications and requirements.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the undesired presence of body fluid in/on the device, which are not part of the documented device specifications and requirements.

NCIt Preferred Term: Device Contamination with Chemical or Other Material
NCIt Definition: Problem associated with contamination of a device with a chemical substance or other non biologic material.
CDRH Preferred Term: Device Contamination with Chemical or Other Material
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with contamination of the device with chemical substance or other non biologic material.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with undesired microbial contamination of the device.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with undesired microbial contamination of the device.

NCIt Preferred Term: Device Contaminated during Manufacturing or Shipping
NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the presence of any unexpected foreign substance found on the surface or in the package materials, which may affect optimal performance for its intended use.
CDRH Preferred Term: Device Contaminated During Manufacture or Shipping
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the presence of any unexpected foreign substance found on the surface or in the package materials, which may affect optimal performance for its intended use, and which occurred during manufacture or shipping.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with a failure during any step of reprocessing process (cleaning, disinfection, packaging, labeling, sterilization) of a used or opened from its original packaging, but unused, device.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with a failure during any step of reprocessing process (cleaning, disinfection, packaging, labeling, sterilization) of a used or opened from its original packaging, but unused, device.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the failure of the device or operator to remove any visible soil, foreign material or organism deposits on the external surfaces, crevices, and joints of the device.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the failure of the device or operator to remove any visible soil, foreign material or organism deposits on the external surfaces, crevices, and joints of the device.

NCIt Definition: Failure to properly disinfect the device during reprocessing.
CDRH Definition: Failure to properly disinfect the device when reprocessing it.

NCIt Definition: Flushing process was not executed properly.
CDRH Definition: Flushing process was not executed properly.

NCIt Preferred Term: Problem with Removal of Enzymatic Cleaner
NCIt Definition: Enzymatic cleaner was not removed properly from the device.
CDRH Preferred Term: Problem with Removal of Enzymatic Cleaner
CDRH Definition: Enzymatic cleaner was not removed properly.

NCIt Definition: Device was not sterilized properly during reprocessing.
CDRH Definition: Device was not sterilized properly during reprocessing.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the decontamination process not adequately removing unwanted visible soil, foreign material, or organism deposits.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the decontamination process not adequately removing unwanted visible soil, foreign material, or organism deposits.

NCIt Preferred Term: Device Contaminated at the User Facility
NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the presence of any unexpected foreign substance found on the surface or in the package materials, which may affect optimal performance for its intended use, and which occurred at the user facility.
CDRH Preferred Term: Device Contaminated at the User Facility
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the presence of any unexpected foreign substance found on the surface or in the package materials, which may affect optimal performance for its intended use, and which occurred at the user facility.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the surrounding conditions in which the device is being used such as temperature, noise, lighting, ventilation, or other external factors such as power supply.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the surrounding conditions in which the device is being used such as temperature, noise, lighting, ventilation, or other external factors such as power supply.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with any undesired acoustic energy or vibration that tends to interfere with the operation of the device.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with any undesired acoustic energy or vibration that tends to interfere with the operation of the device.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with compromised device performance at the ambient temperature or the storage at an inappropriate ambient temperature.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with compromised device performance at the ambient temperature or the storage at an inappropriate ambient temperature.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the visibility, odor, or toxicity of an ambient vapor or gas.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the visibility, odor, or toxicity of an ambient vapor or gas.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the visibility of molds, mildews, yeasts, and/or mushrooms in the immediate environment in which the device is being used.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the visibility of molds, mildews, yeasts, and/or mushrooms in the immediate environment in which the device is being used.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with an unsatisfactory humidity level in the storage or use environment which affects the device performance.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with an unsatisfactory humidity level in the storage or use environment which affects the device performance.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with damage inflicted upon the device from water vapor or water in the immediate environment in which the device is being used.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with damage inflicted upon the device from water vapor or water in the immediate environment in which the device is being used.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the circulation of fresh air in the immediate atmosphere in which the device is being used.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the circulation of fresh air in the immediate atmosphere in which the device is being used.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the visibility of water vapor in the immediate atmosphere in which the device is being used.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the visibility of water vapor in the immediate atmosphere in which the device is being used.

NCIt Preferred Term: Device Unsafe to Use in Environment
NCIt Definition: Problem associated with environmental condition that results in the unsafe use of the device. (e.g. electromagnetic fields, noise, vibration, microbiological contamination etc.).
CDRH Preferred Term: Device Unsafe to Use in Environment
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with environmental condition that results in the unsafe use of the device. (e.g. electromagnetic fields, noise, vibration, microbiological contamination etc.)

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with fine solids or liquid particles such as dust, smoke, fume, and/or mist suspended in the immediate atmosphere in which the device is being used.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with fine solids or liquid particles such as dust, smoke, fume, and/or mist suspended in the immediate atmosphere in which the device is being used.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the facility-supplied medical gases such as medical air, oxygen, nitrous oxide, and nitrogen.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the facility-supplied medical gases such as medical air, oxygen, nitrous oxide, and nitrogen.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the quality of the facility-supplied power to the device.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the quality of the facility-supplied power.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the failure of the facility's emergency power backup system(s) including generators and/or interruptible power systems (UPS).
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the failure of the facility's emergency power backup system(s) including generators and/or interruptible power systems (UPS).

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the failure of primary power supplied by the facility.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the failure of primary power supplied by the facility.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with a momentary overpower/over voltage from the utility and electrical systems of user facilities; or inadequate power conditioning such as the presence of fluctuation, surges, spikes, dropouts, noise and other such undesirable transients.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with a momentary overpower/over voltage from the utility and electrical systems of user facilities; - Problem associated with inadequate power conditioning such as the presence of fluctuation, surges, spikes, dropouts, noise and other such undesirable transients.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with unsatisfactory installation, configuration, and/or setup of a specific device.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with unsatisfactory installation, configuration, and/or setup of a specific device.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the use of the device characterized by incorrect assembly of device components, parts or constituents.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the use of the device characterized by incorrect assembly of device components, parts or constituents.

NCIt Preferred Term: Labeling, Instructions for Use or Training Problem
NCIt Definition: Problem associated with device markings/labeling, instructions for use, training and maintenance documentation or guidelines.
CDRH Preferred Term: Labelling, Instructions for Use or Training Problem
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with device markings/labelling, instructions for use, training and maintenance documentation or guidelines.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the written, printed or graphic material accompanying or affixed to the device or any of its packaging. This includes verbal instructions relating to identification, technical description, and usage provided by a medical device manufacturers. Problems can include but are not limited to this material being unclear, missing, worn out, incorrect or inaccurate.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the written, printed or graphic material accompanying or affixed to the device or any of its packaging. This includes verbal instructions relating to identification, technical description, and usage provided by the device manufacturers. Problems can include but are not limited to this material being unclear, missing, worn out, incorrect or inaccurate.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with errors in identification of expiration date.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with errors in identification of expiration date.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with information unable to be read or deciphered.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with information unable to be read or deciphered.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with imprecise, inexact information.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with imprecise, inexact information.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with ambiguous, confusing information.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with ambiguous, confused information.

NCIt Definition: Absence of information e.g. labeling, instruction for use.
CDRH Definition: Absence of information e.g. labeling, instruction for use.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with an incorrect label being affixed to the device or packaging.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with an incorrect label being affixed to the device or packaging.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with medical device label that looks similar to another product labeling.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with medical device label that looks similar to another product leading to confusion. The other product may be another device or a different product such as a medicine or cleaning agent. Use A020505 for Device packaging look-alike.

NCIt Preferred Term: Lack of Maintenance Documentation or Guidelines
NCIt Definition: Problem associated with user facility not receiving adequate service documentation, guidelines, or recommendations to perform preventative and corrective maintenance and performance assurance checks.
CDRH Preferred Term: Lack of Maintenance Documentation or Guidelines
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with user facility not receiving adequate service documentation, guidelines, or recommendations to perform preventative and corrective maintenance and performance assurance checks.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with inaccuracies in any written, printed, or graphic matter that is affixed to the device or its packaging with any matter that accompanies the device including verbal instructions related to identification, technical description and use of the device provided by the device manufacturers that is intended for healthcare professionals.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with inaccuracies in any written, printed, or graphic matter that is affixed to the device or its packaging with any matter that accompanies the device including verbal instructions related to identification, technical description and use of device provided by the device manufacturers that is intended for healthcare professionals.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with users being unclear and not able to follow any written, printed, or graphic matter that is affixed to device or its packaging with any matter that accompanies a medical device including verbal instructions related to identification, technical description and use of the device provided by a medical device manufacturer that vary from the standard of medical care in a given environment.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with users being unclear and not able to follow any written, printed, or graphic matter that is affixed to device or its packaging with any matter that accompanies the device including verbal instructions related to identification, technical description and use of the device provided by the device manufactures that vary from the standard of medical care in a given environment.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with facility not providing satisfactory initial and/or periodic user training covering operation of a medical device.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with facility not providing satisfactory initial and/or periodic user training covering operation of the device.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with an act or omission of an act that has a different result than that intended by the manufacturer or expected by the operator.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with an act or omission of an act that has a different result than that intended by the manufacturer or expected by the operator.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the use of the device in terms of user experiencing difficulty in preparing device for use, even if the operation is being performed according to labeled instructions for use.
CDRH Preferred Term: Device Difficult to Setup or Prepare
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the use of the device in terms of user experiencing difficulty in preparing device for use, even if the operation is being performed according to labeled instructions for use.

NCIt Definition: The device that is difficult to program, calibrate or set to desired state, even by appropriately trained user/operator.
CDRH Preferred Term: Device Difficult to Program or Calibrate
CDRH Definition: The device is difficult to program, calibrate or set to desired state, even by appropriately trained user/operator.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the user's ability to service a medical device according to the manufacturer specifications relating to a routine device maintenance, i.e., periodic inspection, failure detection, repair, and care of the device to sustain or restore acceptable operating conditions.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the user's ability to service the device according to the manufacturer specifications relating to the device routine maintenance, i.e., periodic inspection, failure detection, repair, and care of the device to sustain or restore acceptable operating conditions.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the means by which the operator and the equipment communicate or interact.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the means by which the operator and the equipment communicate or interact.

NCIt Definition: The device provides a message which is unhelpful or uninformative.
CDRH Definition: The device provides a message which is unhelpful or uninformative, such as an error code without further information about the meaning or appropriate action to take. If the message does not make sense then use A2206 - Device Provides Unintelligible Message.

NCIt Definition: The device provides an unintelligible or incomprehensible message such as an apparently random string of characters.
CDRH Definition: The device provides an unintelligible or incomprehensible message such as an apparently random string of characters. If the message makes sense but is not helpful then use A2205 - Device Provides Uninformative Message.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with failure to process, service, or operate the device according to the manufacturer's recommendations or recognized best practices.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with failure to process, service, or operate the device according to the manufacturer's recommendations or recognized best practices.

NCIt Definition: Handling of the device not in accordance with specification, prior to use on the patient.
CDRH Definition: Handling of the device not in accordance with specification, prior to use on the patient.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the use of the device in terms of inappropriate or incorrect control settings or incorrect treatment parameters for the device's specified operation and/or intended use.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the use of the device in terms of inappropriate or incorrect control settings or incorrect treatment parameters for the device's specified operation and/or intended use.

NCIt Preferred Term: Improper or Incorrect Procedure or Method
NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the use of the device in terms of nonconforming to that device's intended use, specifications, procedure and process or service instructions and information provided by the device manufacturers.
CDRH Preferred Term: Improper or Incorrect Procedure or Method
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the use of the device in terms of nonconforming to that device's intended use, specifications, procedure and process or service instructions and information provided by the device manufacturers.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with the device which has been used for an unapproved indication or for an unapproved intended use.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with the device which has been used for an unapproved indication or for an unapproved intended use.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with incorrect assembly of the device or constituents after being put into use.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with incorrect assembly of the device or constituents after being put into use.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with incorrect assembly of a medical device or constituents by the users.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with incorrect assembly of the device or constituents by the users.

NCIt Definition: Problem associated with incorrect assembly of the device or constituents during maintenance or repair.
CDRH Definition: Problem associated with incorrect assembly of the device or constituents during maintenance or repair.

NCIt Preferred Term: Adverse Event without Identified Device or Use Problem
NCIt Definition: An adverse event appears to have occurred, but there does not appear to have been a problem with a medical device or the way it was used.
CDRH Preferred Term: Adverse Event Without Identified Device or Use Problem
CDRH Definition: An adverse event (e.g. patient harm) appears to have occurred, but there does not appear to have been a problem with the device or the way it was used.

NCIt Definition: Determination of a value is not relevant in the current context.
CDRH Definition: A report has been received but the description provided does not appear to relate to an adverse event. This code allows a report to be recorded for administration purposes, even if it doesn't meet the requirements for adverse event reporting. || Determination of a value is not relevant in the current context.

NCIt Preferred Term: Prophylactic Removal due to Corrective Action
NCIt Definition: Prophylactic removal of a device due to corrective action without malfunction or problem of the specific device involved.
CDRH Preferred Term: Prophylactic removal due to corrective action
CDRH Definition: Prophylactic removal of a device due to corrective action without malfunction or problem of the specific device involved

NCIt Definition: Not yet enough information available to classify the device problem from the adverse event.
CDRH Definition: An adverse event appears to have occurred but there is not yet enough information available to classify the device problem.

NCIt Preferred Term: Appropriate Term/Code Not Available Problem Code
NCIt Definition: A device problem is not adequately described by any other term. Note: this code must not be used unless there is no other feasible code.
CDRH Definition: The device problem is not adequately described by any other term. Note: this code must not be used unless there is no other feasible code. The preferred term should be documented when submitting an adverse event report. This information will be used to determine if a new term should be added to the code table.

NCIt Definition: The investigation employed relevant empirical testing of the actual device suspected in the reported adverse event in order to establish their functional and other properties and to identify possible causes for the adverse event. Relevant testing would typically be based on test methods used for evaluating safety and performance as described in the latest relevant standards.
CDRH Definition: The investigation employed relevant empirical testing of the actual device suspected in the reported adverse event in order to establish their functional and other properties and to identify possible causes for the adverse event. Relevant testing would typically be based on test methods used for evaluating safety and performance as described in the latest relevant standards.

NCIt Preferred Term: Device from Same Lot Evaluated Evaluation Method
NCIt Definition: The investigation employed relevant empirical testing of the device of the same lot or batch than that of the suspected device in the reported adverse event in order to support the identification of possible causes for the adverse event. Testing was performed using the device retained by the manufacturer (i.e. was not shipped). Relevant testing would typically be based on test methods used for evaluating safety and performance as described in the latest relevant standards.
CDRH Preferred Term: Testing of Device from Same Lot/Batch Retained by Manufacturer
CDRH Definition: The investigation employed relevant empirical testing of the device of the same lot or batch than that of the suspected device in the reported adverse event in order to support the identification of possible causes for the adverse event. Testing was performed using the device retained by the manufacturer (i.e. was not shipped). Relevant testing would typically be based on test methods used for evaluating safety and performance as described in the latest relevant standards.

NCIt Preferred Term: Testing of Device from Same Lot/Batch Returned from User
NCIt Definition: The investigation employed relevant empirical testing of the device of the same lot or batch than that of the suspected device in the reported adverse event in order to support the identification of possible causes for the adverse event. The device was returned from the user. Relevant testing would typically be based on test methods used for evaluating safety and performance as described in the latest relevant standards.
CDRH Preferred Term: Testing of Device from Same Lot/Batch Returned from User
CDRH Definition: The investigation employed relevant empirical testing of the device of the same lot or batch than that of the suspected device in the reported adverse event in order to support the identification of possible causes for the adverse event. The device was returned from the user. Relevant testing would typically be based on test methods used for evaluating safety and performance as described in the latest relevant standards.

NCIt Preferred Term: Testing of Device from Other Lot/Batch Retained by Manufacturer
NCIt Definition: The investigation employed relevant empirical testing of the device of another lot or batch than that of the suspected device in the reported adverse event in order to support the identification of possible causes for the adverse event. This includes devices without a lot/batch designation. Testing was performed using the device retained by the manufacturer (i.e. was not shipped). Relevant testing would typically be based on test methods used for evaluating safety and performance as described in the latest relevant standards.
CDRH Preferred Term: Testing of Device from Other Lot/Batch Retained by Manufacturer
CDRH Definition: The investigation employed relevant empirical testing of the device of another lot or batch than that of the suspected device in the reported adverse event in order to support the identification of possible causes for the adverse event. This includes devices without a lot/batch designation. Testing was performed using the device retained by the manufacturer (i.e. was not shipped). Relevant testing would typically be based on test methods used for evaluating safety and performance as described in the latest relevant standards.

NCIt Preferred Term: Testing of Device from Other Lot/Batch Returned from User
NCIt Definition: The investigation employed relevant empirical testing of the device of another lot or batch than that of the suspected device in the reported adverse event in order to support the identification of possible causes for the adverse event. This includes devices without a lot/batch designation. The device was returned from the user. Relevant testing would typically be based on test methods used for evaluating safety and performance as described in the technical file. Relevant testing would typically be based on test methods used for evaluating safety and performance as described in the latest relevant standards.
CDRH Preferred Term: Testing of Device from Other Lot/Batch Returned From User
CDRH Definition: The investigation employed relevant empirical testing of the device of another lot or batch than that of the suspected device in the reported adverse event in order to support the identification of possible causes for the adverse event. This includes devices without a lot/batch designation. The device was returned from the user. Relevant testing would typically be based on test methods used for evaluating safety and performance as described in the technical file or in the latest relevant standards.

NCIt Definition: The investigation employed relevant empirical testing of a model variant of the device involved in the reported adverse event in order to support the identification of possible causes for the adverse event through plausibility reasoning. A model variant is not identical to the actual device, but shares relevant characteristics with the device involved. Relevant testing would typically be based on test methods used for evaluating safety and performance as described in the latest relevant standards.
CDRH Definition: The investigation employed relevant empirical testing of a model variant of the device involved in the reported adverse event in order to support the identification of possible causes for the adverse event through plausibility reasoning. A model variant is not identical to the actual device, but shares relevant characteristics with the device involved. Relevant testing would typically be based on test methods used for evaluating safety and performance as described in the latest relevant standards.

NCIt Definition: The investigation employed relevant empirical testing of the materials used in construction of the device involved in the reported adverse event in order to support the identification of possible causes for the adverse event. Relevant testing would typically be based on test methods used for evaluating safety and performance as described in the latest relevant standards.
CDRH Definition: The investigation employed relevant empirical testing of the materials used in construction of the device involved in the reported adverse event in order to support the identification of possible causes for the adverse event. Relevant testing would typically be based on test methods used for evaluating safety and performance as described in the latest relevant standards.

NCIt Preferred Term: Testing of Patient Sample or Reference Material Using Manufacturer's Device
NCIt Definition: The investigation employed relevant empirical testing of a patient sample or reference material using the device (usually an IVD) involved in the reported adverse event in order to support the identification of possible causes for the adverse event. Relevant testing would typically be based on test methods used for evaluating safety and performance as described in the latest relevant standards.
CDRH Preferred Term: Testing of Patient Sample or Reference Material Using Manufacturer's Device
CDRH Definition: The investigation employed relevant empirical testing of a patient sample or reference material using the device (usually an IVD) involved in the reported adverse event in order to support the identification of possible causes for the adverse event. Relevant testing would typically be based on test methods used for evaluating safety and performance as described in the latest relevant standards.

NCIt Preferred Term: Testing of Patient Sample or Reference Material Using Reference Method
NCIt Definition: The investigation employed relevant empirical testing of a patient sample or reference material using an appropriate reference method to the device (usually an IVD) involved in the reported adverse event in order to support the identification of possible causes for the adverse event. Relevant testing would typically be based on test methods used for evaluating safety and performance as described in the latest relevant standards.
CDRH Preferred Term: Testing of Patient Sample or Reference Material Using Reference Method
CDRH Definition: The investigation employed relevant empirical testing of a patient sample or reference material using an appropriate reference method to the device (usually an IVD) involved in the reported adverse event in order to support the identification of possible causes for the adverse event. Relevant testing would typically be based on test methods used for evaluating safety and performance as described in the latest relevant standards.

NCIt Preferred Term: Testing of Patient Sample or Reference Material Using Competitor's Device
NCIt Definition: The investigation employed relevant empirical testing of a patient sample or reference material using a competitor's device that is comparable to the device (usually an IVD) involved in the reported adverse event in order to support the identification of possible causes for the adverse event. Relevant testing would typically be based on test methods used for evaluating safety and performance as described in the latest relevant standards.
CDRH Preferred Term: Testing of Patient Sample or Reference Material Using Competitor's Device
CDRH Definition: The investigation employed relevant empirical testing of a patient sample or reference material using a competitor's device that is comparable to the device (usually an IVD) involved in the reported adverse event in order to support the identification of possible causes for the adverse event. Relevant testing would typically be based on test methods used for evaluating safety and performance as described in the latest relevant standards.

NCIt Definition: The investigation involved the analysis of historical adverse events data of the actual device involved in the adverse event and/or of products from the same and/or different batches/lots.
CDRH Definition: The investigation involved the analysis of historical adverse events data of the actual device involved in the adverse event and/or of products from the same and/or different batches/lots.

NCIt Definition: The investigation involved trend analysis of adverse event of the actual device involved in the adverse event and/or of products from the same and/or different batches/lots. It should be noted that trend analysis typically is not considered sufficient as a stand-alone method, but should be used in conjunction with other investigation methods for providing for instance complementary information.
CDRH Definition: The investigation involved trend analysis of adverse event of the actual device involved in the adverse event and/or of products from the same and/or different batches/lots. It should be noted that trend analysis typically is not considered sufficient as a stand-alone method, but should be used in conjunction with other investigation methods for providing for instance complementary information.

NCIt Definition: The investigation involved communication/interviews (either interpersonal or through technical means, e.g. phone, e-mail) with persons close to the adverse event, e.g. healthcare professionals (doctors, nurses etc.), the affected patient(s) or other users including, where appropriate, relatives or others engaged in caring for the affected patient.
CDRH Definition: The investigation involved communication/interviews (either interpersonal or through technical means, e.g. phone, e-mail) with persons close to the adverse event, e.g. healthcare professionals (doctors, nurses etc.), the affected patient(s) or other users including, where appropriate, relatives or others engaged in caring for the affected patient.

NCIt Definition: The investigation involved the analysis of relevant production records in view of supporting the identification of possible causes for the adverse event.
CDRH Definition: The investigation involved the analysis of relevant production records in view of supporting the identification of possible causes for the adverse event.

NCIt Preferred Term: Analysis of Information Provided by User/Third Party
NCIt Definition: The investigation involved the analysis of relevant information provided by the user (e.g. healthcare professional, patient, clinical engineer) or a third party (e.g. testing facility) in view of supporting the identification of possible causes for the adverse event.
CDRH Preferred Term: Analysis of Information Provided by User/Third Party
CDRH Definition: The investigation involved the analysis of relevant information provided by the user (e.g. healthcare professional, patient, clinical engineer) or a third party (e.g. testing facility) in view of supporting the identification of possible causes for the adverse event. This does not include information recorded by the device.

NCIt Preferred Term: Device Not Manufactured by Reporting Manufacturer
NCIt Definition: Further information was obtained which established that the manufacturer of the device involved was not the one to which it was initially attributed. This includes mistaken identity or falsified device.
CDRH Preferred Term: Device Not Manufactured by Reporting Manufacturer
CDRH Definition: Further information was obtained which established that the manufacturer of the device involved was not the one to which it was initially attributed. This includes mistaken identity or falsified device. Use in conjunction with C20 and D13 or D14.

NCIt Definition: The actual device involved in the adverse event was not returned for testing despite requests by manufacturer.
CDRH Definition: The actual device involved in the adverse event was not returned for testing despite requests by manufacturer.

NCIt Definition: The actual device involved in the adverse event had been already discarded and thus irretrievably lost for testing.
CDRH Definition: The actual device involved in the adverse event had been already discarded and thus irretrievably lost for testing.

NCIt Definition: The device was returned incompletely, lacking parts, components or accessories that would be required for appropriate testing and analysis of root causes.
CDRH Definition: The device was returned incompletely, lacking parts, components or accessories that would be required for appropriate testing and analysis of root causes.

NCIt Definition: The actual device involved in the adverse event is not readily accessible for testing (e.g. remains implanted in patient).
CDRH Definition: The actual device involved in the adverse event is not readily accessible for testing (e.g. remains implanted in patient).

NCIt Preferred Term: Type of Investigation Not Yet Determined
NCIt Definition: Details to determine the type of investigation are not yet available, but are being sought. Do not use this code if the investigation is complete.
CDRH Preferred Term: Type of Investigation Not Yet Determined
CDRH Definition: Details to determine the type of investigation are not yet available, but are being sought. Do not use this code if the investigation is complete.

NCIt Definition: The information available relating to the reported event is not sufficient to identify either the manufacturer, the device, or other essential information.
CDRH Definition: The information available relating to the reported event is not sufficient to identify either the manufacturer, the device, or other essential information. This term indicates that no further investigation is possible. Do not use this code if further information is being sought, instead use ''Type of investigation not yet determined''.

NCIt Definition: A patient specimen was required to adequately investigate the issue and was requested but not provided.
CDRH Definition: A patient specimen was required to adequately investigate the issue and was requested but not provided.

NCIt Definition: The investigation involved the analysis of the history log files retrieved from the device to support possible causes for the adverse event, includes device interrogation.
CDRH Definition: The investigation involved the analysis of the history log files retrieved from the device to support possible causes for the adverse event, includes device interrogation.

NCIt Definition: Analysis of particulate or foreign material returned from user for evaluation.
CDRH Definition: Analysis of particulate or foreign material returned from user for evaluation.

NCIt Definition: Problems relating to, caused by or affecting biological processes or living organisms.
CDRH Definition: Problems relating to, caused by or affecting biological processes or living organisms.

NCIt Definition: The device causes cellular or tissue responses that elicit an undesirable local or systemic effect in the recipient or beneficiary of that therapy. (See ISO 10993)
CDRH Definition: The device causes cellular or tissue responses that elicit an undesirable local or systemic effect in the recipient or beneficiary of that therapy. (See ISO 10993)

NCIt Definition: The undesirable presence of living organisms such as bacteria, fungi, or viruses or their products (enzymes or toxins).
CDRH Definition: The undesirable presence of living organisms such as bacteria, fungi, or viruses or their products (enzymes or toxins).

NCIt Definition: The undesirable presence of toxins associated with certain bacteria (e.g. gram negative bacteria).
CDRH Definition: The undesirable presence of toxins associated with certain bacteria (e.g. gram negative bacteria).

NCIt Definition: The undesirable presence of microorganisms or microbes such as bacteria and fungi (yeasts and molds).
CDRH Definition: The undesirable presence of microorganisms or microbes such as bacteria and fungi (yeasts and molds).

NCIt Preferred Term: Material or Material Leachate Pyrogenic Problem
NCIt Definition: The undesirable presence of pyrogens or fever-producing organisms caused by materials that permeate through the device.
CDRH Preferred Term: Material or Material Leachate Pyrogenic Problem
CDRH Definition: The undesirable presence of pyrogens or fever-producing organisms caused by materials that permeate through the device.

NCIt Definition: The device was found to have an undesirable level of toxicity to living cells.
CDRH Definition: The device was found to have an undesirable level of toxicity to living cells.

NCIt Definition: The device's ability to cause damage to genetic material (e.g. leading to malignant tumors).
CDRH Definition: The device's ability to cause damage to genetic material (e.g. leading to malignant tumors). (See ISO 10993)

NCIt Definition: The device's ability to trigger development of cancer.
CDRH Definition: The device's ability to trigger development of cancer.
