CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A reduction in the number of red blood cells, the amount of hemoglobin, and/or the volume of packed red blood cells. Clinically, anemia represents a reduction in the oxygen-transporting capacity of a designated volume of blood, resulting from an imbalance between blood loss (through hemorrhage or hemolysis) and blood production. Signs and symptoms of anemia may include pallor of the skin and mucous membranes, shortness of breath, palpitations of the heart, soft systolic murmurs, lethargy, and fatigability.
CDRH Definition: A reduction in the number of red blood cells, the amount of hemoglobin, and/or the volume of packed red blood cells.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Anemia resulting from the premature destruction of the peripheral blood red cells. It may be congenital or it may be caused by infections, medications, or malignancies.
CDRH Definition: Anemia resulting from the premature destruction of the peripheral blood red cells.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A condition in which there is a deviation from or interruption of the normal coagulation properties of the blood.
CDRH Definition: A condition in which there is a deviation from or interruption of the normal coagulation properties of the blood.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A pathological process where the blood starts to coagulate throughout the whole body. This depletes the body of its platelets and coagulation factors, and there is an increased risk of hemorrhage.
CDRH Definition: A pathological process where the blood starts to coagulate throughout the whole body. This depletes the body of its platelets and coagulation factors, and there is an increased risk of hemorrhage.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A laboratory test result indicating that there is an abnormally small number of platelets in the circulating blood.
CDRH Definition: Low blood platelet count.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Disruption of the integrity of the erythrocyte membrane causing release of hemoglobin.
CDRH Definition: Disruption of the integrity of the erythrocyte membrane causing release of hemoglobin.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Fluid accumulation in tissues and body cavities.
CDRH Definition: An abnormally high circulating blood volume.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Abnormally decreased volume of circulating fluid (plasma) in body.
CDRH Definition: An abnormally low circulating blood volume.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: The presence of pathogenic microorganisms in the blood stream causing a rapidly progressing systemic reaction that may lead to shock. Symptoms include fever, chills, tachycardia, and increased respiratory rate. It is a medical emergency that requires urgent medical attention.
CDRH Definition: The presence of pathogenic microorganisms in the blood stream causing a rapidly progressing systemic reaction that may lead to shock. Symptoms include fever, chills, tachycardia, and increased respiratory rate. It is a medical emergency that requires urgent medical attention.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A collection of serum in the body.
CDRH Definition: A tumor-like collection of serum in the tissues.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: The presence of an enlarged lymph node.
CDRH Definition: The presence of an enlarged lymph node.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A lower than average level of leukocytes in a sample.
CDRH Definition: The white blood cell count is below the normal range, including neutropenia.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A problem with the blood or lymphatic system.
CDRH Definition: The report describes a non-specific problem with the blood or lymphatic system. Note: Please use "Appropriate Term / Code Not Available" if the report describes a specific problem but the relevant term does not exist.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A laboratory test result indicating an increased number of white blood cells in the peripheral blood.
CDRH Definition: The white blood cell count is above the normal range.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Adverse events associated with the transfusion of whole blood or one of its components, most commonly a hemolytic reaction to cross-typed blood.
CDRH Definition: Adverse events associated with the transfusion of whole blood or one of its components, most commonly a hemolytic reaction to cross-typed blood.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: One or more of the blood protein levels being higher or lower than normal (e.g. Albumin, C-reactive Protein).
CDRH Definition: One or more of the blood protein levels being higher or lower than normal (e.g. Albumin, C-reactive Protein).

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A disorder resulting from loss of function or tissue destruction of an organ or multiple organs, arising from humoral or cellular immune responses of the individual to his own tissue constituents. It may be systemic (e.g., systemic lupus erythematosus), or organ specific, (e.g., thyroiditis).
CDRH Definition: A disorder resulting from loss of function or tissue destruction of an organ or multiple organs, arising from humoral or cellular immune responses of the individual to his own tissue constituents.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An immune response that occurs following exposure to an innocuous antigen, but that does not require the presence of preformed antibodies to the antigen.
CDRH Definition: A local or general reaction of an organism following contact with a specific allergen to which it has been previously exposed and to which it has become sensitized.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Progression of anaphylaxis into systemic shock, which is characterized by significant reduction in tissue perfusion which leads to hypoxia and hypotension, and can lead to death if untreated.
CDRH Definition: Progression of anaphylaxis into systemic shock, which is characterized by significant reduction in tissue perfusion which leads to hypoxia and hypotension, and can lead to death if untreated.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Acute immune response that occurs from exposure to an allergen. It can be anaphylaxis or like anaphylaxis
CDRH Definition: Acute immune response that occurs from exposure to an allergen. For conditions which have progressed to systemic shock, use E040201 - Anaphylactic Shock.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A regionally-limited response to an antigen, which may include inflammation, induration, erythema, pruritus or pain.
CDRH Definition: A regionally-limited response to an antigen, which may include inflammation, induration, erythema, pruritus or pain.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Syndromes in which there is a deficiency or defect in the mechanisms of immunity, either cellular or humoral.
CDRH Definition: A deficiency of immune response or a disorder characterized by deficient immune response.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Indicates that antibodies directed against nuclear antigens have been detected.
CDRH Definition: Indicates that antibodies directed against nuclear antigens have been detected. Almost invariably found in systemic lupus erythematosus and are frequently found in rheumatoid arthritis, scleroderma, Sjogren's Syndrome and mixed connective tissue disease.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A disorder resulting from an abnormality in the immune system.
CDRH Definition: The report describes a non-specific problem with the immune system. Note: Please use "Appropriate Term / Code Not Available" if the report describes a specific problem but the relevant term does not exist.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Bulging or ballooning in an area of an artery secondary to arterial wall weakening.
CDRH Definition: Bulging or ballooning in an area of an artery secondary to arterial wall weakening.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An aneurysm that has burst, resulting in hemorrhage into adjacent tissues.
CDRH Definition: An aneurysm that has burst, resulting in hemorrhage into adjacent tissues.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Expansion of aneurysm.
CDRH Definition: Expansion of aneurysm.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A vascular disorder characterized by thickening and hardening of the walls of the arteries.
CDRH Definition: A vascular disorder characterized by thickening and hardening of the walls of the arteries. Build-up of fatty material and calcium deposition in the arterial wall resulting in partial or complete occlusion of the arterial lumen.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: The blockage of a blood vessel lumen by air or solid material such as blood clot or other tissues (e.g., adipose tissue, cancer cells) that have migrated from another anatomic site.
CDRH Definition: The blockage of a blood vessel lumen by air or solid material such as blood clot or other tissues (e.g., adipose tissue, cancer cells) that have migrated from another anatomic site.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: The presence of bubbles of air in the vascular system; occurrence is related to the entry of air into the venous circulation following trauma or surgery.
CDRH Definition: The presence of bubbles of air in the vascular system; occurrence is related to the entry of air into the venous circulation following trauma or surgery.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Occlusion of a lumen by a foreign object.
CDRH Definition: Type of embolism when lumen of vessel or ductus is occluded by part of device.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: The obstruction of the pulmonary artery or one of its branches by an embolus, sometimes associated with infarction of the lung.
CDRH Definition: The obstruction of the pulmonary artery or one of its branches by an embolus, sometimes associated with infarction of the lung.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Occlusion of the lumen of a vessel by a thrombus that has migrated from a distal site via the blood stream.
CDRH Definition: Occlusion of the lumen of a vessel by a thrombus that has migrated from a distal site via the blood stream.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: The blockage of a blood vessel by fat particles in the circulation.
CDRH Definition: The blockage of a blood vessel by fat particles in the circulation.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: The leakage of body fluid or cells from the vascular system to the surrounding tissues. This process occurs either by force or as a result of a pathologic reaction (e.g., inflammation). This process may sometimes allow cancer cells to migrate from capillaries to adjacent tissues, initiating micro-metastases.
CDRH Definition: The leakage of body fluid or cells from the vascular system to the surrounding tissues. This process occurs either by force or as a result of a pathologic reaction (e.g., inflammation).

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A localized collection of blood, usually clotted, in an organ, space, or tissue, due to a break in the wall of a blood vessel.
CDRH Definition: A localized collection of blood, usually clotted, in an organ, space, or tissue, due to a break in the wall of a blood vessel.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: The flow of blood from a ruptured blood vessel.
CDRH Definition: The loss of blood from the circulation, including blood loss from a device connected to a patient.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A flat discoloration of the skin or a mucous membrane, larger in area than a petechia, caused by the extravasation of blood.
CDRH Definition: A flat discoloration of the skin or a mucous membrane, larger in area than a petechia, caused by the extravasation of blood. Discolouration under the skin caused by a bleed underneath. Typically a bruise.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Extensive loss of blood due to internal or external hemorrhage.
CDRH Definition: Extensive loss of blood due to internal or external hemorrhage.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: The measurement of the mean left arterial pressure, as measured by a catheter introduced into the distal pulmonary artery, is high.
CDRH Definition: The measurement of the mean left atrial pressure, as measured by a catheter introduced into the distal pulmonary artery, is high.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: The measurement of the mean left pulmonary arterial pressure, as measured by a catheter introduced into the distal pulmonary artery, is low.
CDRH Definition: The measurement of the mean left atrial pressure, as measured by a catheter introduced into the distal pulmonary artery, is low.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Lack of blood supply to an area of the body, resulting in impairment of tissue oxygenation.
CDRH Definition: Lack of oxygen in tissues, commonly due to impaired blood supply to an area of the body, resulting in impairment of tissue oxygenation.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: The formation of new or recent blood vessels. The vasculature network is critical to the development of neoplasms. As the tumor burden grows, vascular endothelial cells are recruited to form new blood vessels as an increased demand for blood and nourishment is required.
CDRH Definition: The formation of new blood vessels.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Damage to a blood vessel resulting from a full thickness disruption in the integrity of the vessel wall.
CDRH Definition: Damage to a blood vessel resulting from a full thickness disruption in the integrity of the vessel wall.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Damage to the venae cavae, pulmonary artery, pulmonary veins or aorta resulting from a full thickness disruption in the integrity of the vessel wall.
CDRH Definition: Damage to the venae cavae, pulmonary artery, pulmonary veins or aorta resulting from a full thickness disruption in the integrity of the vessel wall.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An inflammatory process involving the wall of the vessels (large, medium, or small-sized vessels). The inflammatory process may cause necrosis or formation of granulomas in the vascular wall. It may be the result of an autoimmune disorder, infection, or malignancy. Representative examples include polyarteritis nodosa, temporal arteritis, Wegener granulomatosis, Kawasaki disease, Takayasu arteritis, and Henoch-Schonlein purpura.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: The creation of hematoma outside the arterial wall following bleeding due to puncture of the arterial wall. Pseudoaneurysms can also occur in the heart chambers following myocardial infarction and bleeding.
CDRH Definition: The creation of hematoma outside the arterial wall following bleeding due to puncture of the arterial wall. Pseudoaneurysms can also occur in the heart chambers following myocardial infarction with rupture of the wall of the ventricle.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An aggregation of blood factors, primarily platelets and fibrin with entrapment of cellular elements, frequently causing vascular obstruction at the point of its formation.
CDRH Definition: The formation of a blood clot in the lumen of a vessel or heart chamber.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: The process of cutting apart or separating tissue, usually for further analysis or study.
CDRH Definition: Spontaneous or induced tear within the wall of a blood vessel.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A progressive tear in the tissue lining the aorta, characterized by the passage of blood from the tunica intima into, and partially through, the tunica media.
CDRH Definition: Spontaneous or induced tear within the wall of the aorta

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Vasoconstriction involves narrowing of a blood vessel lumen due to smooth muscle contraction in the vessel wall and leads to decreased blood flow.
CDRH Definition: Vasoconstriction involves narrowing of a blood vessel lumen due to smooth muscle contraction in the vessel wall and leads to decreased blood flow.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Vasodilation involves widening of a blood vessel lumen due to smooth muscle relaxation in the vessel wall and leads to increased blood flow.
CDRH Definition: Widening of a blood vessel lumen due to smooth muscle relaxation in the vessel wall and leads to increased blood flow.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A non-neoplastic or neoplastic disorder affecting the arteries, veins, or lymphatic vessels. Examples include vasculitis, thrombophlebitis, arteriosclerosis, lymphedema, hemangioma, and angiosarcoma.
CDRH Definition: The report describes a non-specific problem with the vascular system. Note: Please use "Appropriate Term / Code Not Available" if the report describes a specific problem but the relevant term does not exist.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Inadequate blood flow.
CDRH Definition: Inadequate blood flow to a particular area of the body.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Tissue damage caused when blood supply returns to tissue after a period of ischemia or lack of oxygen. The restoration of circulation results in inflammation and oxidative damage.
CDRH Definition: Tissue damage caused when blood supply returns to tissue after a period of ischemia or lack of oxygen. The restoration of circulation results in inflammation and oxidative damage.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Partial or total occlusion or obstruction of the coronary ostia or artery.
CDRH Definition: Partial or total occlusion or obstruction of the coronary ostia or artery.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Any variation from the normal rate or rhythm (which may include the origin of the impulse and/or its subsequent propagation) in the heart.
CDRH Definition: Any variation from the normal rate or rhythm (which may include the origin of the impulse and/or its subsequent propagation) in the heart.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An electrocardiographic finding showing no cardiac electrical activity on the monitor or printed strip for the entire duration of the recording. (CDISC)
CDRH Definition: An electrocardiographic finding showing a state of cardiac standstill with no cardiac output and no ventricular depolarization.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A disorder characterized by an electrocardiographic finding of a supraventricular arrhythmia characterized by the replacement of consistent P waves by rapid oscillations or fibrillatory waves that vary in size, shape and timing and are accompanied by an irregular ventricular response. (CDISC)
CDRH Definition: Irregular heart rhythm, usually associated with a rapid rate, that is caused by abnormal electrical activity within the atrial.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A disorder characterized by an electrocardiographic finding of an organized, regular atrial rhythm with atrial rate of 240-340 beats per minute. Multiple P waves typically appear in the inferior leads in a saw tooth-like pattern between the QRS complexes. (CDISC)
CDRH Definition: A rapid heart rate, associated with a regular rhythm, that is caused by abnormal electrical activity within the atria.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An abnormally slow heart rate. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist.
CDRH Definition: An abnormally slow heart rate. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A cardiac beat originating from an abnormal site.
CDRH Definition: A cardiac beat originating from an abnormal site. These changes lead to extra or dropped heartbeats.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An electrocardiographic finding of blocked cardiac electrical impulses along the fibers normally responsible for impulse conduction.
CDRH Definition: An interference with the normal conduction of electrical impulses that control activity of the heart muscle.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An electrocardiographic finding of three or more consecutive complexes of ventricular origin with a rate less than a certain threshold (100 or 120 beats per minute are commonly used). The QRS complexes are wide and have an abnormal morphology. (CDISC)
CDRH Definition: An electrocardiographic finding of three or more consecutive complexes of ventricular origin. The QRS complexes are wide and have an abnormal morphology. (CDISC)

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Not rhythmic pulse irregular in beat or accent.
CDRH Definition: A pulse that beats at irregular intervals.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An abnormally rapid heart rate. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist.
CDRH Definition: Abnormally high heart rate. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A disorder characterized by an electrocardiographic finding of a rapid grossly irregular ventricular rhythm with marked variability in QRS cycle length, morphology, and amplitude. The rate is typically greater than 300 bpm. (CDISC)
CDRH Definition: Arrhythmia characterized by chaotic contractions of the ventricular muscle.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: The sudden cessation of cardiac activity in an individual who becomes unresponsive, without normal breathing and no signs of circulation. Cardiac arrest may be reversed by CPR, and/or defibrillation, cardioversion or cardiac pacing.
CDRH Definition: The sudden cessation of productive cardiac activity in an individual who becomes unresponsive, without normal breathing and no signs of circulation.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An increase from the normal levels of cardiac enzymes measurement.
CDRH Definition: Increase from the normal levels of cardiac enzymes.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: The presence of an acquired hole in the heart. Cardiac perforation may or may not be symptomatic and may or may not be self sealing. (ACC)
CDRH Definition: The presence of an acquired hole in the heart.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Acute compression of the heart caused by increased intrapericardial pressure due to the collection of blood or fluid in the pericardium from rupture of the heart, penetrating trauma, or progressive effusion.
CDRH Definition: Acute compression of the heart caused by increased intrapericardial pressure due to the accumulation of blood or fluid in the pericardium from rupture of the heart or great vessels, penetrating trauma, or progressive effusion.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A disease of the heart muscle or myocardium proper. Cardiomyopathies may be classified as either primary or secondary, on the basis of etiology, or on the pathophysiology of the lesion: hypertrophic, dilated, or restrictive.
CDRH Definition: A disease of the heart muscle.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Circulatory dysfunction and/or insufficiency due to a decrease in the force of the cardiac contractions and/or the tone of the vascular walls.
CDRH Definition: Circulatory dysfunction/insufficiency due to a decrease in the force of the cardiac contractions and/or the tone of the vascular walls. Includes diastolic and systolic dysfunction.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A split located on a leaflet of a heart valve that prevents its complete closing, which can result in valvular dysfunction.
CDRH Definition: A tear located on a leaflet of a heart valve that prevents its complete closing, which can result in valvular dysfunction.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Weak or absent palpable pulse due to decreased arterial pulse pressure.
CDRH Definition: Weak or absent palpable pulse due to decreased arterial pulse pressure.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Inflammation of the endocardium.
CDRH Definition: Inflammation of the endocardium.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Failure of the heart to pump a sufficient amount of blood to meet the needs of the body tissues, resulting in tissue congestion and edema. Signs and symptoms include shortness of breath, pitting edema, enlarged tender liver, engorged neck veins, and pulmonary rales.
CDRH Definition: Inability of the heart to pump blood adequately to fill tissue metabolic requirements or the ability to do so only at an elevated filling pressure.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A disorder of cardiac function caused by insufficient blood flow to the muscle tissue of the heart. The decreased blood flow may be due to narrowing of the coronary arteries, to obstruction by a thrombus, or less commonly, to diffuse narrowing of arterioles and other small vessels within the heart. Severe interruption of the blood supply to the myocardial tissue may result in necrosis of cardiac muscle (myocardial infarction).
CDRH Definition: A disorder of cardiac function caused by insufficient blood flow to the muscle tissue of the heart. The decreased blood flow may be due to narrowing of the coronary arteries, to obstruction by a thrombus, or less commonly, to diffuse narrowing of arterioles and other small vessels within the heart. Severe interruption of the blood supply to the myocardial tissue may result in necrosis of cardiac muscle (myocardial infarction).

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Paroxysms of chest pain due to reduced oxygen to the heart.
CDRH Definition: Chest pain resulting from inadequate oxygen delivery for the needs of the myocardium.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Gross necrosis of the myocardium, as a result of interruption of the blood supply to the area, as in coronary thrombosis.
CDRH Definition: A condition which occurs when blood flow decreases or stops to a part of the heart, causing damage to the heart muscle.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A below normal volume of blood pumped from the right or left ventricle of the heart per unit time.
CDRH Definition: A below normal volume of blood pumped from the right or left ventricle of the heart per unit time.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A rupture in the mitral valve tissue due to traumatic or pathologic processes.
CDRH Definition: A rupture in the mitral valve tissue due to traumatic or pathologic processes.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A bruise to the heart.
CDRH Definition: A bruise to the heart.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Thickening of the myocardium often due to chronic pressure overload.
CDRH Definition: Thickening of the myocardium often due to chronic pressure overload.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Inflammation of the muscle tissue of the heart.
CDRH Definition: Inflammation of the muscle tissue of the heart.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a change in cardiac electrical activity.
CDRH Definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a change in cardiac electrical activity.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Fluid collection within the pericardial sac, usually due to inflammation.
CDRH Definition: Fluid collection within the pericardial sac, usually due to inflammation.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An inflammatory process affecting the pericardium.
CDRH Definition: Inflammation of the pericardium.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Dysfunction of one of the cardiac valves characterized by incomplete valve closure.
CDRH Definition: Dysfunction of one of the cardiac valves, with incomplete valve closure or damage to a valve leaflet resulting in valvular backflow.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Dysfunction of the aortic valve characterized by incomplete valve closure.
CDRH Definition: Incomplete closure or damage to a valve leaflet of the aortic valve, resulting in aortic valve backflow.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Dysfunction of the mitral valve characterized by incomplete valve closure.
CDRH Definition: Incomplete closure or damage to a valve leaflet of the mitral valve, resulting in mitral valve backflow.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Dysfunction of the pulmonary valve characterized by incomplete valve closure.
CDRH Definition: Incomplete closure or damage to a valve leaflet of the pulmonary valve, resulting in pulmonary valve backflow.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Dysfunction of the pulmonary valve characterized by incomplete valve closure.
CDRH Definition: Incomplete closure or damage to a valve leaflet of the tricuspid valve, resulting in tricuspid valve backflow.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Narrowing of the opening of one or more of the four valves of the heart.
CDRH Definition: Obstruction of flow across a heart valve due to immobility of the leaflets and/or a restricted orifice.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Narrowing of the orifice of the aortic valve.
CDRH Definition: Obstruction of flow across a aortic heart valve due to immobility reduced elasticity of the leaflets and/or a restricted orifice.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Narrowing of the left atrioventricular mitral orifice.
CDRH Definition: Obstruction of flow across a mitral heart valve due to immobility reduced elasticity of the leaflets and/or a restricted orifice.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Narrowing of the opening between the pulmonary artery and the right ventricle, usually at the level of the valve leaflets.
CDRH Definition: Obstruction of flow across a pulmonary heart valve due to immobility reduced elasticity of the leaflets and/or a restricted orifice.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Narrowing or stricture of the tricuspid orifice of the heart.
CDRH Definition: Obstruction of flow across a tricuspid heart valve due to immobility reduced elasticity of the leaflets and/or a restricted orifice.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A non-neoplastic or neoplastic disorder that affects the heart and/or the pericardium. Representative examples include endocarditis, pericarditis, atrial myxoma, cardiac myeloid sarcoma, and pericardial malignant mesothelioma.
CDRH Definition: The report describes a non-specific problem with the heart. Note: Please use "Appropriate Term / Code Not Available" if the report describes a specific problem but the relevant term does not exist.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An intraoperative event that causes abnormal valve function; this is usually a tear in the leaflet or the chordae tendinae.
CDRH Definition: An intraoperative event that causes abnormal valve function; this is usually a tear in the leaflet or the chordae tendinae.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Irregular blood flow in the heart after surgical correction of a septal defect.
CDRH Definition: Irregular blood flow in the heart after surgical correction of a septal defect.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Increased pressure across the heart valve.
CDRH Definition: Increased pressure across the heart valve

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Damage to the heart during a surgical procedure.
CDRH Definition: An intraoperative event that causes abnormal cardiac function. For valvular injury, use E0624 - Intraoperative Cardiac Valve Injury

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Progressive and life-threatening pulmonary distress in the absence of an underlying pulmonary condition, usually following major trauma or surgery. Cases of neonatal respiratory distress syndrome are not included in this definition.
CDRH Definition: Progressive and life-threatening pulmonary distress in the absence of an underlying pulmonary condition, usually following major trauma or surgery. Cases of neonatal respiratory distress syndrome are not included in this definition.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Blockage of air flow in the respiratory tract.
CDRH Definition: Blockage of air flow in the respiratory tract.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Transient cessation of respiration.
CDRH Definition: Transient cessation of respiration.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A disorder characterized by inhalation of solids or liquids into the lungs.
CDRH Definition: The entry of foreign material past the trachea, and into the lower respiratory tract.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Inflammation of the lungs due to the inhalation of solid or liquid material.
CDRH Definition: Inflammation of the lungs due to the inhalation of solid or liquid material.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A chronic respiratory disease manifested as difficulty breathing due to the narrowing of bronchial passageways.
CDRH Definition: A chronic respiratory disease manifested as difficulty breathing due to the narrowing of bronchial passageways.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Bleeding from the bronchial wall and/or lung parenchyma.
CDRH Definition: Bleeding from the bronchial wall and/or lung parenchyma.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An acute or chronic inflammatory process affecting the bronchi.
CDRH Definition: An acute or chronic inflammatory process affecting the bronchi.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Sudden contraction of the smooth muscles of the bronchial wall.
CDRH Definition: Sudden contraction of the smooth muscles of the bronchial wall.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Interference with respiration by compression or obstruction of the larynx or trachea.
CDRH Definition: Interference with respiration by obstruction of the larynx or trachea.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A chronic and progressive lung disorder characterized by the loss of elasticity of the bronchial tree and the air sacs, destruction of the air sacs wall, thickening of the bronchial wall, and mucous accumulation in the bronchial tree. The pathologic changes result in the disruption of the air flow in the bronchial airways. Signs and symptoms include shortness of breath, wheezing, productive cough, and chest tightness. The two main types of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease are chronic obstructive bronchitis and emphysema.
CDRH Definition: A chronic and progressive lung disorder characterized by the loss of elasticity of the bronchial tree and the air sacs, destruction of the air sacs wall, thickening of the bronchial wall, and mucous accumulation in the bronchial tree. The pathologic changes result in the disruption of the air flow in the bronchial airways. Signs and symptoms include shortness of breath, wheezing, productive cough, and chest tightness. The two main types of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease are chronic obstructive bronchitis and emphysema.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A subcategory of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD). It occurs in people who smoke and suffer from chronic bronchitis. It is characterized by inflation of the alveoli, alveolar wall damage, and reduction in the number of alveoli, resulting in difficulty breathing.
CDRH Definition: A condition characterized by increase beyond normal in the size of air spaces distal to the terminal bronchioles, either from dilatation of the alveoli or from destruction of their walls.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A sudden, often repetitive, spasmodic contraction of the thoracic cavity, resulting in violent release of air from the lungs, and usually accompanied by a distinctive sound.
CDRH Definition: A sudden, often repetitive, spasmodic contraction of the thoracic cavity, resulting in violent release of air from the lungs, and usually accompanied by a distinctive sound.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Decreased expiratory peak flow measurement achieved during forced expiration that primarily reflects changes in upper airway conductance and may be of limited use in evaluation of changes in peripheral airway conductance. Evaluation of peak flow performance is subjective, and, therefore, acceptability criteria are lacking. Because the maneuver is effort and volume dependent, the patient must be encouraged to perform as vigorously as clinically feasible. The results of subjective evaluation may be difficult to interpret consistently. A validated dyspnea rating scale may be useful.
CDRH Definition: Decrease in the maximum flow rate generated during a forceful exhalation, starting from full lung inflation.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An increase of the greatest rate of flow that can be achieved during forced expiration beginning with the lungs fully inflated.
CDRH Definition: An increase of the greatest rate of flow that can be achieved during forced expiration beginning with the lungs fully inflated.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Abnormal decrease of rate of breathing.
CDRH Definition: Abnormal decrease of rate of breathing.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Abnormal increase of rate of breathing.
CDRH Definition: Abnormal increase of rate of breathing.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An uncomfortable sensation of difficulty breathing. It may present as an acute or chronic sign of an underlying respiratory or heart disorder.
CDRH Definition: An uncomfortable sensation of difficulty breathing. It may present as an acute or chronic sign of an underlying respiratory or heart disorder.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Bleeding from the nose.
CDRH Definition: Nose bleed.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A decrease in the fraction of the forced vital capacity that is exhaled in a specific number of seconds.
CDRH Definition: A decrease in the fraction of the forced vital capacity that is exhaled in a specific number of seconds.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An increase in the fraction of the forced vital capacity that is exhaled in a specific number of seconds.
CDRH Definition: An increase in the fraction of the forced vital capacity that is exhaled in a specific number of seconds.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Coughing up blood from the respiratory tract.
CDRH Definition: Coughing up blood from the respiratory tract.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A collection of blood in the pleural cavity.
CDRH Definition: A collection of blood in the pleural cavity.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An involuntary contraction of the diaphragm against closed vocal cords, producing the "hic" sound.
CDRH Definition: An involuntary contraction of the diaphragm against closed vocal cords, producing the hic sound.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Abnormally prolonged, rapid, and deep breathing.
CDRH Definition: Abnormally prolonged, rapid, and deep breathing.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A state in which there is a reduced amount of air entering the pulmonary alveoli.
CDRH Definition: A state in which there is a reduced amount of air entering the pulmonary alveoli.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A decrease in the amount of oxygen in the body. Symptoms range from mild (impaired judgment, memory loss, impaired motor coordination) to severe (seizures and coma).
CDRH Definition: A deficiency in the amount of oxygen reaching the tissues.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Displacement of structures in the thoracic cavity in one direction due to increased pleural pressure on the contralateral side.
CDRH Definition: Displacement of structures in the thoracic cavity in one direction due to increased pleural pressure on the contralateral side.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Blockage of the nasal passages.
CDRH Definition: Blockage of the nasal passages.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Abnormal permanent enlargement of the lung air spaces distal to terminal bronchiole not resulted from wall destruction, e.g. due to loss of opposite lung.
CDRH Definition: Abnormal permanent enlargement of the lung air spaces distal to terminal bronchiole not resulted from wall destruction, e.g. due to loss of opposite lung.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Inflammation of the throat most often caused by viral and bacterial infections. Other causes include allergens, chemical substances, and trauma.
CDRH Definition: Inflammation of the throat most often caused by viral and bacterial infections.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Increased amounts of fluid within the pleural cavity. Symptoms include shortness of breath, cough, and chest pain. It is usually caused by lung infections, congestive heart failure, pleural and lung tumors, connective tissue disorders, and trauma.
CDRH Definition: Increased amounts of fluid within the pleural cavity. Symptoms include shortness of breath, cough, and chest pain.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An accumulation of pus in the pleural space.
CDRH Definition: An accumulation of pus in the pleural space

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An acute, acute and chronic, or chronic inflammation focally or diffusely affecting the lung parenchyma, due to infections (viruses, fungi, mycoplasma, or bacteria), treatment (e.g. radiation), or exposure (inhalation) to chemicals. Symptoms include cough, shortness of breath, fevers, chills, chest pain, headache, sweating, and weakness.
CDRH Definition: An acute and/or chronic inflammation focally or diffusely affecting the lung parenchyma.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Acute inflammation of the walls of the terminal bronchioles that spreads into the peribronchial alveoli and alveolar ducts.  It results in the creation of foci of consolidation, which are surrounded by normal parenchyma. It affects one or more lobes, and is frequently bilateral and basal.  It is usually caused by bacteria (e.g., Staphylococcus, Streptococcus, Haemophilus influenzae).  Signs and symptoms include fever, cough with production of brown-red sputum, dyspnea, and chest pain.
CDRH Definition: Acute inflammation of the walls of the terminal bronchioles.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Abnormal presence of air in the pleural cavity.
CDRH Definition: Abnormal presence of air in the pleural cavity.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Impaired or abnormal functioning of the pulmonary system.
CDRH Definition: Impaired or abnormal functioning of the pulmonary system causing multiple pulmonary issues.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Accumulation of fluid in the lung tissues causing disturbance of the gas exchange that may lead to respiratory failure. It is caused by direct injury to the lung parenchyma or congestive heart failure. The symptoms may appear suddenly or gradually. Suddenly appearing symptoms include difficulty breathing, feeling of suffocation, and coughing associated with frothy sputum. Gradually appearing symptoms include difficulty breathing while lying in bed, shortness of breath during activity, and weight gain (in patients with congestive heart failure).
CDRH Definition: Accumulation of fluid in the lung tissues causing disturbance of the gas exchange that may lead to respiratory failure.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Increased pressure within the pulmonary circulation due to lung or heart disorder.
CDRH Definition: Increased pressure within the pulmonary circulation due to lung or heart disorder.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Localized necrosis of lung tissue caused by obstruction of the arterial blood supply, most often due to pulmonary embolism.
CDRH Definition: Localized necrosis of lung tissue caused by obstruction of the arterial blood supply, most often due to pulmonary embolism.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A condition in which the blood pH is less than normal, secondary to impaired gas exchange.
CDRH Definition: A condition in which the blood pH is less than normal, secondary to impaired gas exchange.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A condition in which the blood pH is greater than normal, secondary to impaired gas exchange.
CDRH Definition: A condition in which the blood pH is greater than normal, secondary to impaired gas exchange.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Cessation of breathing function.
CDRH Definition: Cessation of breathing function.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: The significant impairment of gas exchange within the lungs resulting in hypoxia, hypercarbia, or both, to the extent that organ tissue perfusion is severely compromised. Causes include chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, asthma, emphysema, acute respiratory distress syndrome, pneumonia, pulmonary edema, pneumothorax, and congestive heart failure. Treatment requires intubation and mechanical ventilation until the time the lungs recover sufficient function.
CDRH Definition: The significant impairment of gas exchange within the lungs resulting in hypoxia, hypercarbia, or both, to the extent that organ tissue perfusion is severely compromised.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Impairment of gas exchange within the lungs secondary to a disease process, neoplasm, or trauma, possibly resulting in hypoxia, hypercarbia, or both, but not requiring intubation or mechanical ventilation. Patients are normally managed with pharmaceutical therapy, supplemental oxygen, or both.
CDRH Definition: Impairment of gas exchange within the lungs secondary to a disease process, neoplasm, or trauma, possibly resulting in hypoxia, hypercarbia, or both.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An infectious process affecting the upper respiratory tract (nose, paranasal sinuses, pharynx, larynx, or trachea). Symptoms include congestion, sneezing, coughing, fever, and sore throat.
CDRH Definition: An infectious disease affecting the respiratory tract.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A rupture in the sinus tissue due to traumatic or pathologic processes.
CDRH Definition: A rupture in the sinus tissue due to traumatic or pathologic processes.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A symptom consisting of the involuntary expulsion of air from the nose.
CDRH Definition: A symptom consisting of the involuntary expulsion of air from the nose.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Any kind of inflammatory process of the tonsils, pharynx, or/and larynx characterized by pain in swallowing.
CDRH Definition: Any kind of inflammatory process of the tonsils, pharynx, or/and larynx characterized by pain in swallowing.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Condition where there are a greater number of inhalations relative to the number of exhalations.
CDRH Definition: Condition where there are a greater number of inhalations relative to the number of exhalations.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Choking or arrest of respiration due to occlusion of the air passages; arrest of circulation in a part due to compression.
CDRH Definition: Interference with respiration by compression of the larynx, laryngopharynx or trachea, as well as of the carotid arteria or jugular veins.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A condition that requires mechanical life support due to inability to breath effectively to maintain normal levels of oxygen and carbon dioxide in the body.
CDRH Definition: A condition that requires mechanical life support due to inability to breath effectively to maintain normal levels of oxygen and carbon dioxide in the body.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A high pitched breathing sound that results from restricted airways.
CDRH Definition: A symptom and finding during physical examination, characterized by high-pitched, whistling sound during breathing. It results from narrowing or obstruction of the respiratory airways. Also known as stridor.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A non-neoplastic or neoplastic disorder that affects the respiratory system. Representative examples include pneumonia, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, pulmonary failure, lung adenoma, lung carcinoma, and tracheal carcinoma.
CDRH Definition: The report describes a non-specific problem with the respiratory system. Note: Please use "Appropriate Term / Code Not Available" if the report describes a specific problem but the relevant term does not exist.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Mechanical or chemical injuries to the upper airways, including trachea, pharynx and larynx.
CDRH Definition: Mechanical or chemical injuries to the upper airways, including trachea, pharynx and larynx.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Irritation and swelling of the upper airways.
CDRH Definition: Irritation and swelling of the upper airways

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A harsh inspiratory sound during sleep.
CDRH Definition: A particular type of noisy sound made by air passage across relaxed tissues during sleep.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: The blockage of the nasal passage due to mucosal edema. It is usually the result of a viral infection or an allergic reaction.
CDRH Definition: The blockage of the nasal passage due to mucosal edema. It is usually the result of a viral infection or an allergic reaction.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A group of breathing disorders characterized by abnormal respiratory patterns or insufficient ventilation during sleep.
CDRH Definition: Clinical spectrum with frequent episodes of either complete or partial obstruction of the upper airway during sleep. Includes sleep apnea. Also known as Sleep disordered breathing (SDB).

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An inflammation of the mucous membrane lining the nose, usually associated with nasal discharge.
CDRH Definition: Pattern of symptoms as a result of nasal inflammation and/or dysfunction of the nasal mucosa. There are various subtypes, such as allergic, infectious and non-allergic (e.g. atrophic) rhinitis.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A tear in the capsular bag housing the lens of the eye.
CDRH Definition: A tear in the capsular bag housing the lens.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Partial or complete opacity of the crystalline lens of one or both eyes that decreases visual acuity and eventually results in blindness. Some cataracts appear in infancy or in childhood, but most develop in older individuals. (Sternberg Diagnostic Surgical Pathology, 3rd ed.)
CDRH Definition: Partial or complete opacity of the crystalline lens of one or both eyes that decreases visual acuity and eventually results in blindness. Some cataracts appear in infancy or in childhood, but most develop in older individuals. (Sternberg Diagnostic Surgical Pathology, 3rd ed.)

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Edema of the mucous membrane of the eyeball and eyelid lining.
CDRH Definition: Edema of the mucous membrane of the eyeball and eyelid lining.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Inflammation of the conjunctiva of the eye.
CDRH Definition: Inflammation of the conjunctiva of the eye.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Opacity within the cornea.
CDRH Definition: Clouding of the middle area of the cornea, usually as a result of scarring due to infection, injury, or inflammation.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Endothelial decompensation that is manifested by opacity of the cornea. The condition often occurs as a nonspecific response to mechanical injury from incidental corneal contact by intraocular instruments during surgery; chemical injury from the improper use of intraocular drugs, drugs containing preservatives, or from residues from inadequate rinsing of detergents or other residues from surgical instruments. The most common causes of corneal endothelial decompensation in the adult population are cataract removal/IOL-related endothelial loss and Fuchs dystrophy. When severe, corneal endothelial decompensation requires corneal transplantation.
CDRH Definition: Inability to maintain corneal integrity; or corneal edema resulting from failure of the corneal endothelium to maintain detumescence.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Hazy, swollen cornea.
CDRH Definition: Hazy, swollen cornea.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Fluid from the aqueous humor enters the corneal stroma and causes swelling.
CDRH Definition: Fluid from the aqueous humor enters the corneal stroma and causes swelling.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Corneal edema of inflammatory origin associated with contact lens wear and morphologically characterized by presence of epithelial microcysts. Microcysts are small (typically 10-50 microns in diameter), clear, irregularly shaped high refractive inclusions that form in the basal layers of the epithelium and move towards the anterior surface of the cornea, surrounding epithelial haze. The cause of microcytic edema is related to the physical presence of contact lenses and possibly a mechanical effect of lens wear.
CDRH Definition: Corneal edema of inflammatory origin associated with contact lens wear and morphologically characterized by presence of epithelial microcysts.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Very small, round vesicles containing fluid and cellular debris observed on the surface of the cornea under slit-lamp examination in some types of corneal dystrophy and in wearers of extended-wear lenses.
CDRH Definition: Very small, round vesicles containing fluid and cellular debris observed on the surface of the cornea under slit lamp examination in some types of corneal dystrophy and in wearers of extended wear lenses.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Discrete, small lesions present in the cornea as a result of corneal inflammation and, in some cases, after soft contact lens wear especially extended-wear lenses.
CDRH Definition: Discrete, small lesions present in the cornea as a result of corneal inflammation and, in some cases, after soft contact lens wear especially extended-wear lenses.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Superficial vascularization of the cornea with infiltration of granulation tissue; an inflammatory exudate overlying the lining layer of synovial cells on the inside of a joint.
CDRH Definition: Superficial vascularization of the cornea with infiltration of granulation tissue.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A rupture in the corneal tissue due to traumatic or pathologic processes
CDRH Definition: A rupture in the corneal tissue due to traumatic or pathologic processes.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Replacement of corneal tissue with scar tissue as a result of injury to the deeper layers of the cornea.
CDRH Definition: Replacement of corneal tissue with scar tissue as a result of injury to the deeper layers of the cornea.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Complications of intraocular lens surgery; usually refers to intraocular lens contact with cornea, can be intermittent or chronic.
CDRH Definition: Complications of intraocular lens surgery; usually refers to intraocular lens contact with cornea, can be intermittent or chronic.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Area of epithelial tissue loss from corneal surface; associated with inflammatory cells in the cornea and anterior chamber.
CDRH Definition: Area of epithelial tissue loss from corneal surface; associated with inflammatory cells in the cornea and anterior chamber.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A syndrome characterized by dryness of the cornea and conjunctiva. It is usually caused by a deficiency in tear production. Symptoms include a feeling of burning eyes and a possible foreign body presence in the eye.
CDRH Definition: A syndrome characterized by dryness of the cornea and conjunctiva. It is usually caused by a deficiency in tear production. Symptoms include a feeling of burning eyes and a possible foreign body presence in the eye.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An infectious process affecting the internal structures of the eye.
CDRH Definition: Inflammation of the intraocular fluids or tissues usually with microbial organisms.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Excessive tearing of the eyes due to either tear overproduction or impaired drainage of the tear ducts. Causes of tear overproduction include eye irritation (e.g., eye infection, foreign body in the eye), headache, pain reaction, allergies, sinusitis, and injury to the eye.
CDRH Definition: Profuse lacrimation.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An infectious process affecting any part of the eye. Causes include viruses and bacteria. Symptoms include itching and discomfort in the eye, watery eyes, eye pain and discharge, and blurring vision. Representative examples include pink eye, blepharitis, and trachoma.
CDRH Definition: An infection of any part of the eye, including the eyelid.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Infection within the eye.
CDRH Definition: Infection within the eye.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Damage to the eye.
CDRH Definition: Damage to the eye.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Injury to the epithelium of the cornea.
CDRH Definition: Injury to the epithelium of the cornea.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Chemical or radiant injury to the cornea.
CDRH Definition: Burn injury, including chemical burn, to any part of the eye.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An eye emergency condition which may lead to blindness if left untreated. It is characterized by the separation of the inner retina layers from the underlying pigment epithelium. Causes include trauma, advanced diabetes mellitus, high myopia, and choroid tumors. Symptoms include sudden appearance of floaters, sudden light flushes, and blurred vision.
CDRH Definition: Separation of the inner retina layers from the underlying pigment epithelium.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Injury to the retina due to advanced age, toxicity, exposure to bright lights, or trauma.
CDRH Definition: Damage to the retina due to toxicity, exposure to bright lights, or trauma.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A usually small tearing of the retina occurring when the vitreous separates from the retina. It may lead to retinal detachment. Symptoms include flashes and floaters.
CDRH Definition: A usually small tearing of the retina occurring when the vitreous separates from the retina. It may lead to retinal detachment.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: The separation of the vitreous from the retina.
CDRH Definition: Detachment of the vitreous humor from the retina.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Painful sensation in the eye.
CDRH Definition: Painful sensation in the eye.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Feeling of grittiness or having something in the eye; frequently caused by a foreign body. Other possible causes include corneal abrasion, corneal ulcer, inturned eye lash or acute conjunctivitis.
CDRH Definition: Feeling of grittiness or having something in the eye; frequently caused by a foreign body.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Increased pressure in the eyeball due to obstruction of the outflow of aqueous humor.
CDRH Definition: Increased pressure in the eyeball due to obstruction of the outflow of aqueous humor.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Hazy ring around bright lights seen by some patients with refractive error or optical defects, e.g. cataracts, or corneal swelling.
CDRH Definition: Hazy ring around bright lights seen by some patients with refractive error or optical defects, e.g. cataracts, or corneal swelling.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Hemorrhage within the anterior chamber of the eye; bloodshot.
CDRH Definition: Hemorrhage within the anterior chamber of the eye.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An accumulation of pus in the anterior chamber of the eye.
CDRH Definition: An accumulation of pus in the anterior chamber of the eye.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Decrease of pressure of the intraocular fluid in the eye.
CDRH Definition: Decrease of pressure of the intraocular fluid in the eye.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Increased pressure of the intraocular fluid in the eye.
CDRH Definition: Increase of pressure of the intraocular fluid in the eye, also known as ocular hypertension.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Inflammation of the iris.
CDRH Definition: Inflammation of the iris.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Inflammation of the cornea.
CDRH Definition: Inflammation of the cornea.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Inflammation of the cornea secondary to an infectious process.
CDRH Definition: Keratitis due to infection, including infection by acanthamoeba.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Accumulation of intraretinal fluid and protein in the macula, which may result in swelling and decreased central vision.
CDRH Definition: Accumulation of intraretinal fluid and protein in the macula, which may result in swelling and decreased central vision.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Ocular pain which may be very intense, accompanied by corneal epithelium damage, conjunctival injection, lacrimation, blepharospasm, photophobia and hazy vision following corneal edema caused by overwear of contact lenses, principally the PMMA type.
CDRH Definition: Ocular pain which may be very intense, accompanied by corneal epithelium damage, conjunctival injection, lacrimation, blepharospasm, photophobia and hazy vision following corneal edema caused by overwear of contact lenses, principally the PMMA type.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An obstruction of the pupil.
CDRH Definition: An obstruction of the pupil.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Lay term applied to any condition with dilation of conjunctival or ciliary blood vessels; innumerable causes, especially irritation and infection.
CDRH Definition: Lay term applied to any condition with dilation of conjunctival or ciliary blood vessels; innumerable causes.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Degeneration of the retina.
CDRH Definition: Degeneration of the retina.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An acute postoperative inflammatory reaction in which a noninfectious substance enters the anterior segment of the eye and induces toxic damage to the intraocular tissues.
CDRH Definition: An acute postoperative inflammatory reaction in which a noninfectious substance enters the anterior segment and induces toxic damage to the intraocular tissues.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Clinical triad of uveitis, glaucoma, and hyphema (UGH), especially associated with the early anterior chamber intraocular lens (IOL). Glaucoma is believed to be caused by movement of the IOL against the iris causing release of inflammatory and red blood cell debris, which obstruct the trabecular meshwork. The haptic also may cause direct damage to the trabecular meshwork contributing to the glaucoma. Incidence of UGH is dependent on both surgical methodology applied in the cataract population and type of IOL used. UGH is particularly common if metal clip lenses have been used. Components of the condition may be reversed if the offending IOL is removed before permanent damage has occurred.
CDRH Definition: Clinical triad of uveitis, glaucoma, and hyphema (UGH), especially associated with the insertion of an anterior chamber intraocular lens (IOL).

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions

Causes include inflammatory agents (e.g., herpes simplex, herpes zoster, leptospirosis) and systemic diseases (e.g., inflammatory bowel disease, multiple sclerosis, systemic lupus erythematosus, ankylosing spondylitis). Patients present with pain and redness in the eye, light sensitivity, and blurred and decreased vision.
CDRH Definition: Inflammation of the uvea.

NCIt Definition: An interference to normal eyesight.

NCIt Definition: The perception of sudden or brief bursts (flashes) of light.

NCIt Definition: Blood extravasation in the vitreous humor. Causes include neovascularization, retinal tear, retinal detachment, and rupture of a blood vessel aneurysm in the eye.

NCIt Definition: Loss or prolapse of vitreous gel.
CDRH Definition: loss or prolapse of vitreous gel.

NCIt Definition: Inflammatory intraocular reaction with clouding and cells in vitreous; often accompanies inflammation of ciliary body, iris, choroid, or retina.
CDRH Definition: Inflammatory intraocular reaction with clouding and cells in vitreous; often accompanies inflammation of ciliary body, iris, choroid, or retina.

NCIt Definition: Rupture of the fibrous strands connecting the ciliary body and the crystalline lens of the eye.
CDRH Definition: Rupture of the fibrous strands connecting the ciliary body with the crystalline lens of the eye (usually at the time of cataract surgery).

CDRH Definition: A generic term used to describe abnormal sensations that bother the eyes like dryness, itchiness, burning and grittiness.

CDRH Definition: A change in the shape of the corneal surface presenting as abnormal radial symmetry.

CDRH Definition: Partial or complete loss of the ability to detect or understand sounds resulting from damage to the outer, middle, or inner ear structures.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A feeling of movement, a sensation as if the external world were revolving around the patient (objective vertigo) or as if he himself were revolving in space (subjective vertigo). Vertigo is medically distinct from dizziness, lightheadedness, and unsteadiness.
CDRH Definition: A feeling of movement, a sensation as if the external world were revolving around the person or as if they were revolving in space (subjective vertigo). Vertigo is medically distinct from dizziness, lightheadedness, and unsteadiness.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions

CDRH Definition: Infection of the ear.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Inflammation of the anatomical structures of the outer ear and ear canal secondary to an infectious process. Bacterial etiology is most common, but fungal infection is also possible. Symptoms include erythema, edema, and pain.
CDRH Definition: An infectious process involving the outer ear and ear canal.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Inflammation of the anatomical structures of the middle ear secondary to an infectious process. Bacterial etiology is most common, but both viral and fungal pathogens are also possible. Symptoms include erythema and edema of the tympanic membrane, pain, and possibly fever. In severe infections, inflammation and edema of the structures of the middle ear can lead to perforation of the tympanic membrane secondary to the buildup of pressure in the narrow space.
CDRH Definition: An infectious process involving the middle ear, includes acute otitis media, chronic otitis media, chronic suppurative otitis media, otitis media with effusion (OME), etc.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Inflammation of the anatomical structures of the middle ear, which is most often caused by an infectious process. Symptoms include erythema and edema of the tympanic membrane, pain, and possibly fever.
CDRH Definition: Inflammation (swelling and redness) to the middle ear.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Inflammation of the anatomical structures of the inner ear secondary to an infectious process. Symptoms include severe vertigo, nausea, vomiting, anxiety, and pain. Viral etiology is most common, and recent history of an upper respiratory infection is common.
CDRH Definition: An inflammation of the labyrinth in the inner ear that causes dizziness and reduced or distorted hearing.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions

NCIt Definition: Vomiting blood.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Bleeding within the abdominal cavity.

The most common cause of esophageal perforation is injury during a medical procedure such as esophagoscopy or placement of a naso-gastric tube; and pathologic process such as neoplasm or gastric reflux with ulceration. Less common causes include injuries from penetrating or blunt trauma or injury to the esophagus during an operation on another organ, mechanical problem such as violent retching or vomiting; ingestion of a foreign body or caustic agents. The condition often results in infection of the mediastinum and mediastinitis.
