CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: One or more teeth lost/dislodged from the mouth.
CDRH Definition: One or more teeth lost/dislodged from the mouth.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Painful inflammation of the bursa. It most often affects the hips, shoulders, and elbows.
CDRH Definition: Inflammation of the fluid-filled pad (bursa).

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Trauma to cartilage.
CDRH Definition: Damage of cartilage.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A painful condition caused by the friction of joint tissues.
CDRH Definition: Impingement relating to joints. Can be e.g. implant-on-bone, implant-on-soft tissue, or implant-on-implant impingement.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Inflammation of the mucosal lining of the mastoid antrum and mastoid air cell system of the mastoid process.
CDRH Definition: An infection of the bony air cells in the mastoid bone.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Painful sensation in the upper or lower extremities.
CDRH Definition: Pain in the arms and/or legs.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A congenital or acquired deformity of the spine. Representative examples include scoliosis, kyphosis, and sagittal imbalance.
CDRH Definition: Abnormal curvature and/or alignment of the spine.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A disorder of the tendons with signs/symptoms of pain, diffuse or localized swelling and impaired performance.
CDRH Definition: Overuse tendon injuries characterized by a combination of pain, diffuse or localized swelling, and impaired performance. Problems include tendonitis/tendinitis and tendinosis, as well as tendon tears and inflammation of membranes around a tendon

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Elevated pressure in a confined space enclosed by fascia or eschar, which may lead to vascular compromise and subsequent ischemic injury to the tissue within the space.
CDRH Definition: Condition in which a closed muscle compartment's pressure increases to such an extent that the circulation is diminished, e.g. due to decrease in a compartment volume or an increase in the contents of a compartment, or both.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Bleeding into a joint.
CDRH Definition: Bleeding into the joints

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An indentation at the edge of the bone without bone breakage.
CDRH Definition: An indentation made at the edge of the bone without bone breakage.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Non-neoplastic overgrowth of bone.
CDRH Definition: Benign hypertrophy that projects outward from the surface of bone, often containing a cartilaginous component, such as bone spurs/osteophytes.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Acetabular defect with a shift of the femoral head through the pelvis.
CDRH Definition: Acetabular defect with a shift of the femoral head through the pelvic bone.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Air trapped in the subcutaneous space. It can be palpated or heard as a crackling or grating sensation under the skin.
CDRH Definition: Grating sound or sensation produced by friction between e.g. bone, cartilage, fractured parts of a bone.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Any disorder of the joints.
CDRH Definition: Diseases and disorders of a joint (e.g. Rotator cuff arthropathy, cuff tear arthropathy (CTA)) More specific codes and terms should be used where they exist e.g. E1602 - Arthritis

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Painful sensation in the back region.
CDRH Definition: Pain in any part of the back.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Superficial damage to the skin caused by rubbing or scraping.
CDRH Definition: Superficial damage to the skin caused by rubbing or scraping.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Rapid swelling of the deep layers of the skin due to transient vascular leakage of serous fluid.
CDRH Definition: Rapid swelling of the deep layers of the skin due to transient vascular leakage of serous fluid.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An intraepidermal/subepidermal cavity filled with clear, serosanguineous or cloudy fluid.
CDRH Definition: A collection of fluid underneath the top layer of skin.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A traumatic injury involving interruption of tissue cohesiveness that results from exposure to caustic chemicals, extreme heat, extreme cold or excessive radiation.
CDRH Definition: An injury or tissue damage caused by exposure to caustic chemicals, extreme heat, extreme cold or excessive radiation.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A burn caused by exposure to chemical substances.
CDRH Definition: A burn caused by exposure to chemical substances.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Local tissue damage due to exposure to extreme cold.
CDRH Definition: Local tissue damage due to exposure to extreme cold.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A burn caused by exposure to x-ray, radium, sunlight, atomic or any other type of radiant energy.
CDRH Definition: A burn caused by exposure to x-ray, radium, sunlight, ionizing radiation or any other type of radiant energy.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A painful injury to the epidermis due to chemical, friction, radiation or thermal exposure. The affected area appears red and blanches when touched.
CDRH Definition: A burn that affects the epidermis only, causing erythema without blistering.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An injury that includes the entire epidermis and upper layers of the dermis due to a chemical, friction, radiation or thermal exposure. The affected area appears as moist red or white skin that does not blanch. Often it is painful with the presence of blisters.
CDRH Definition: A burn that affects the epidermis and the dermis.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An injury that includes all skin layers into the subcutaneous tissue due to chemical, friction, radiation or thermal exposure. The affected area appears dry and thickened; damage to nerve endings usually renders the wound painless.
CDRH Definition: A burn to the skin that extends into deeper layers and underlying tissues.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A sensation of stinging or heat, not necessarily accompanied by redness or physical signs of irritation.
CDRH Definition: A sensation of stinging or heat, not necessarily accompanied by redness or physical signs of irritation.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A sensation of dermal stinging or heat, not necessarily accompanied by redness or physical signs of skin irritation.
CDRH Definition: A sensation of dermal stinging or heat, not necessarily accompanied by redness or physical signs of skin irritation.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Preferred Term: Tumor Cell Seeding related to Procedure
NCIt Definition: The spread of benign or malignant tissue during medical or surgical procedures.
CDRH Definition: Spreading benign or malignant tissue during medical procedures.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Improper body tissue repair due to factors affecting one or more of the phases of wound healing.
CDRH Definition: Improper repair of any body tissue due to factors affecting one or more of the phases of wound healing. Includes impaired healing of any body tissue.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An intense itching sensation.
CDRH Definition: An irritating feeling that produces the desire to scratch.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Yellow pigmentation of the skin, mucous membranes, and the eyes due to hyperbilirubinemia. Causes include liver disease, biliary tract obstruction, and hemolysis.
CDRH Definition: Yellow pigmentation of the skin, mucous membranes, and the eyes due to hyperbilirubinemia.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A pathologic process that affects the skin and is confined to a specific area.
CDRH Definition: A pathologic process that affects the skin and is confined to a specific area.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A peeling off or loss of epidermis, as in sunburn, postscarlatinal peeling, or toxic epidermal necrolysis.
CDRH Definition: A peeling off or loss of epidermis, as in sunburn, postscarlatinal peeling, or toxic epidermal necrolysis.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A nonimmunologic, chemically induced type of photosensitivity.
CDRH Definition: A nonimmunologic, chemically induced type of photosensitivity.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Erosion of patient's skin pocket which houses a device.
CDRH Definition: Erosion of patient's tissue pocket which houses a device.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Any change in the skin which affects its appearance or texture. A rash may be localized to one part of the body, or affect all the skin. Rashes may cause the skin to change color, itch, become warm, bumpy, dry, cracked or blistered, swell and may be painful.
CDRH Definition: An eruption in the skin which effects its appearance and/or texture.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Formation of new tissue formed in the healing of a wound.
CDRH Definition: Formation of new tissue formed in the healing of a wound.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A benign, epidermal skin lesion characterized by overexpression of collagen during wound healing.
CDRH Definition: Excessive or unusual scarring related to impaired wound healing (e.g. Keloid or Hypertrophic scar)

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Abnormal skin coloration.
CDRH Definition: any abnormal change in skin coloration.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Red discoloration of the skin caused by infectious agents, inflammation, drug hypersensitivity, or underlying disease.
CDRH Definition: Red discoloration of the skin.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Darkening of the skin due to excessive melanin deposition. Causes include skin injuries, pregnancy, eczema, and Addison disease.
CDRH Definition: Darkening of the skin due to excessive melanin deposition.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Abnormal lightening of skin due to decreased melanin production or deposition. Vitiligo, albinism, and leukoderma are among the disorders that are associated with skin hypopigmentation.
CDRH Definition: Abnormal lightening of skin due to decreased melanin production or deposition.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Any deviation from the normal structure or function of the skin or subcutaneous tissue that is manifested by a characteristic set of symptoms and signs.
CDRH Definition: Affecting the skin.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Tearing or wearing off of skin.
CDRH Definition: A gradual breakdown or very shallow ulceration of the skin which involves only the epidermis and heals without scarring.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An inflammatory process affecting the skin, caused by bacteria, viruses, parasites, or fungi. Examples of bacterial infection include carbuncles, furuncles, impetigo, erysipelas, and abscesses. Examples of viral infection include shingles, warts, molluscum contagiosum, and pityriasis rosea. Examples of parasitic infection include scabies and lice. Examples of fungal infection include athlete's foot, yeast infection, and ringworm.
CDRH Definition: An inflammatory process affecting the skin, caused by bacteria, viruses, parasites, or fungi.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An inflammatory process affecting the skin. Signs include red rash, itching, and blister formation. Representative examples are contact dermatitis, atopic dermatitis, and seborrheic dermatitis.
CDRH Definition: An inflammatory process affecting the skin. Signs include red rash, itching, and blister formation. Representative examples are contact dermatitis, atopic dermatitis, and seborrheic dermatitis.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An inflammatory process characterized by the accumulation of pus within a newly formed tissue cavity which is the result of a bacterial, fungal, or parasitic infection or the presence of a foreign body.
CDRH Definition: An inflammatory process characterized by the accumulation of pus within a newly formed tissue cavity.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Inflammation of the dermis and subcutaneous tissues caused by a bacterial infection. Symptoms include erythema, edema, and pain to the affected area.
CDRH Definition: Inflammation of the dermis and subcutaneous tissues caused by a bacterial infection.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An inflammatory skin condition caused by direct contact between the skin and either an irritating substance or an allergen.
CDRH Definition: An inflammatory skin condition caused by direct contact between the skin and either an irritating substance or an allergen.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A form of dermatitis characterized by red, itchy, scaly, or crusty patches that can be chronic or intermittent.
CDRH Definition: A form of dermatitis characterized by red, itchy, scaly, or crusty patches that can be chronic or intermittent.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A cutaneous inflammatory reaction occurring as a result of exposure to biologically effective levels of ionizing radiation.
CDRH Definition: A cutaneous inflammatory reaction occurring as a result of exposure to biologically effective levels of ionizing radiation.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A transient, itchy skin eruption characterized by wheals with pale interiors and red margins.
CDRH Definition: A transient, itchy skin eruption characterized by wheals with pale interiors and red margins.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A smooth, slightly elevated area on the body surface, which is redder or paler than the surrounding skin. It is the typical lesion of urticaria, the dermal evidence of allergy, and in sensitive persons may be provoked by mechanical irritation of the skin.
CDRH Definition: A smooth, slightly elevated area on the body surface, which is redder or paler than the surrounding skin.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A break in skin tissue caused by friction or shearing.
CDRH Definition: A break in skin tissue caused by friction or shearing.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A small palpable mass in the subcutaneous tissues.
CDRH Definition: A small palpable abnormal mass in the subcutaneous tissues.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A fold, ridge or crease of the skin.
CDRH Definition: A folding, ridge or creasing of the skin.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: The pores are generally fine with a papery thin texture that feels dry to the touch. Usually flaky and dull looking.
CDRH Definition: Skin that has become dry in texture and flaky.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Liquid or a pocket of air trapped under the skin, typically due to injection procedures.
CDRH Definition: Liquid or a pocket of air trapped under the skin, typically due to injection problems. Does not include inflammation.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Softening and whitening of the skin due to excessive moisture.
CDRH Definition: Softening of tissue by the action of a liquid. Occurs at the wound site/surrounding areas due to excessive moisture from exudate or products applied.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Malodorous smell of the wound.
CDRH Definition: Malodor of the wound or skin not otherwise explained. Can include odors due to necrosis, bioburden or other barriers to wound healing.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Alteration of the normal characteristics of the fingernails or toenails. Examples include thickening, thinning, deformity, and separation from the nail bed.
CDRH Definition: Abnormality of the nail, such as problems with the color, shape, texture, or thickness of the fingernails or toenails.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A neoplasm composed of atypical neoplastic, often pleomorphic cells that invade other tissues. Malignant neoplasms often metastasize to distant anatomic sites and may recur after excision. The most common malignant neoplasms are carcinomas, Hodgkin and non-Hodgkin lymphomas, leukemias, melanomas, and sarcomas.
CDRH Definition: A group of diseases in which abnormal cells divide without control, invade nearby tissues and may also spread to other parts of the body through the blood and lymph systems.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A carcinoma arising from the breast, most commonly the terminal ductal-lobular unit. It is the most common malignant tumor in females. Risk factors include country of birth, family history, menstrual and reproductive history, fibrocystic disease and epithelial hyperplasia, exogenous estrogens, contraceptive agents, and ionizing radiation. The vast majority of breast carcinomas are adenocarcinomas (ductal or lobular). Breast carcinoma spreads by direct invasion, by the lymphatic route, and by the blood vessel route. The most common site of lymph node involvement is the axilla.
CDRH Definition: A malignant neoplasm that develops or arises in breast tissue.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Preferred Term: Breast Implant-Associated Anaplastic Large Cell Lymphoma
NCIt Definition: A rare anaplastic large cell lymphoma that develops in individuals with breast implants. It usually presents as an accumulation of seroma fluid between the implant and the surrounding fibrous capsule. The median interval from the time of the implant to the development of lymphoma is approximately 10 years.
CDRH Preferred Term: Breast Implant Associated Anaplastic Large Cell Lymphoma (BIA ALCL)
CDRH Definition: A non-Hodgkin lymphoma which is associated with breast implants, and consists of large anaplastic cells. The WHO diagnostic criteria for BIA-ALCL includes positive expression of CD30 (CD30+) and negativity for anaplastic lymphoma kinase (ALK-).

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An uncommon, aggressive malignant smooth muscle neoplasm, usually occurring in post-menopausal women.  It is characterized by a proliferation of neoplastic spindle cells.  Morphologic variants include epithelioid, granular cell, inflammatory and myxoid leimyosarcomas.
CDRH Definition: A malignant tumor of smooth muscle cells that can arise almost anywhere in the body but is most common in the uterus, abdomen, or pelvis.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A malignant (clonal) proliferation of B- lymphocytes or T- lymphocytes which involves the lymph nodes, bone marrow and/or extranodal sites. This category includes Non-Hodgkin lymphomas and Hodgkin lymphomas.
CDRH Definition: A malignant (clonal) proliferation of B- lymphocytes or T- lymphocytes which involves the lymph nodes, bone marrow and/or extranodal sites. This category includes Non-Hodgkin lymphomas and Hodgkin lymphomas.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A morphologic finding indicating the presence of cystic structures in a tissue sample.
CDRH Definition: A sac-like closed membranous structure that may be empty or contain fluid or amorphous material.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A small lump, swelling or collection of tissue.
CDRH Definition: A small lump, swelling or collection of tissue.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A benign or malignant neoplasm arising from tissues that do not include fluid areas.  Representative examples include epithelial neoplasms (e.g. lung carcinoma, prostate carcinoma, breast carcinoma, colon carcinoma), and neoplasms arising from the soft tissues and bones (e.g. leiomyosarcoma, liposarcoma, chondrosarcoma, osteosarcoma).  Neoplasms originating from the blood or bone marrow (leukemias and myeloproliferative disorders) are not considered solid tumors.
CDRH Definition: Abnormal mass of tissue that usually does not contain cysts or liquid areas. Solid tumours may be benign (not cancerous), or malignant (cancerous). Different types of solid tumours are named for the type of cells that form them. If tumours are associated with those under the term cancer, these terms should be used.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A category that includes benign neoplasms and neoplasms with uncertain malignant potential. The latter are characterized by clinicopathological features that are not benign, including some degree of mild or mild/moderate atypia/dysplasia, but lack overt malignant morphologic characteristics and there is no evidence of metastasis at the time of diagnosis.
CDRH Definition: A new and abnormal growth of tissue in a part of the body which is not indicative of malignant disorder. Can include benign tumors.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An acute infectious disorder that is caused by gram positive or gram negative bacteria; representative examples include pneumococcal, streptococcal, salmonella, and meningeal infections.
CDRH Definition: An acute infectious disorder caused by gram positive or gram negative bacteria.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A bacterial infection that is resistant to antibiotics and antimicrobials.
CDRH Definition: An infection that is resistant to antibiotics and antimicrobials, for example, MRSA or VRE.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An infection caused by pus-producing organisms.
CDRH Definition: An infection caused by pus-producing organisms.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: The condition resulting from the spread of bacterial products (toxins) by the bloodstream.
CDRH Definition: The condition resulting from the spread of bacterial products (toxins) by the bloodstream.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An infection caused by a fungus.
CDRH Definition: An infection caused by a fungus.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A disorder acquired through sexual contact.
CDRH Definition: A disease acquired predominantly through sexual contact.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Infection associated with no detectable symptoms but caused by microorganisms capable of producing easily recognizable diseases, such a poliomyelitis or mumps.
CDRH Definition: Infection associated with no detectable signs or symptoms but caused by microorganisms capable of producing easily recognizable diseases.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A transmissible, infectious disease that is caused by a protein that is able to induce abnormal folding of normal cellular proteins, leading to characteristic spongiform brain changes, which are associated with neuronal loss without an inflammatory response. Such disorders have typically long incubation periods, but are then generally rapidly progressive and are uniformly fatal.
CDRH Definition: A group of rare degenerative brain disorders associated with prions for example Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease (CJD) or Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy (BSE).

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A disorder resulting from the presence and activity of a microbial, viral, fungal, or parasitic agent. It can be transmitted by direct or indirect contact.
CDRH Definition: The report describes a non-specific or unidentified infection. Note: Please use the appropriate term if the report describes a specific infection. i.e. Bacterial Infection E1901, Fungal Infection E1902, Viral Infection E1907, or a relevant Level 3 term where more detail is available.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Any disease caused by a virus.
CDRH Definition: Any disease caused by a virus.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A genus of the family herpesviridae, subfamily betaherpesvirinae, infecting the salivary glands, liver, spleen, lungs, eyes, and other organs, in which they produce characteristically enlarged cells with intranuclear inclusions.
CDRH Definition: A genus of the family herpesviridae, subfamily betaherpesvirinae, infecting the salivary glands, liver, spleen, lungs, eyes, and other organs, in which they produce characteristically enlarged cells with intranuclear inclusions.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Shedding of accumulated bone fragments.
CDRH Definition: Shedding of accumulated bone fragments.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Injury of the soft tissues or bone without breaking the skin that is characterized by blood leakage into the surrounding area.
CDRH Definition: Injury of the soft tissues without breaking the skin that is characterized by blood leakage into the surrounding area.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Contact with a chemical substance through touch, inhalation, or ingestion.
CDRH Definition: Contact with a chemical substance through touch, inhalation, or ingestion.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Traumatic compression of the body or a part of the body.
CDRH Definition: Traumatic compression of the body or a part of the body.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Appearance of skin bruises following perceived minimal contact or injury.
CDRH Definition: Appearance of bruises spontaneously or following minimal contact.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An eating away or breakdown of any type of external or internal human tissue including but not limited to skin, teeth, mucosa, or somatic, which involves only the outer tissue layer. When tissue surrounds an implanted device, the tissue breakdown may result in migration and loss of the implant material and may result in further complications such as infection or abscess.
CDRH Definition: An eating away or breakdown of any type of external or internal human tissue including but not limited to skin, teeth, mucosa, or somatic, which involves only the outer tissue layer. When tissue surrounds an implanted device, the tissue breakdown may result in migration and loss of the implant material and may result in further complications such as infection or abscess.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A sudden movement downward, usually resulting in injury.
CDRH Definition: A sudden movement downward, usually resulting in injury.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Extraneous material within the body.
CDRH Definition: An occurrence where any object including device or fragments is left unintentionally in the body.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Issue associated with the inability to retrieve device and/or device fragments during medical procedures.
CDRH Preferred Term: Device Embedded In Tissue or Plaque
CDRH Definition: Device and/or fragments of device are embedded in patient's tissue and/or plaque.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A cut or tear in any tissue.
CDRH Definition: A cut or tear in any tissue.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A penetrating stab wound from a needle (or other sharp object) that may result in exposure to blood or other body fluids.
CDRH Definition: A penetrating stab wound from a needle (or other sharp object) that may result in exposure to blood or other body fluids.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Patient becomes entangled or caught in a bed, particularly in side rails, or mattress, or head/foot boards.
CDRH Definition: Patient becomes entangled or trapped in a device.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Infection of a break in the skin or other tissue.
CDRH Definition: Infection of a wound. This does not include post surgical wound infection.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Forcible tearing or disruption of tissue.
CDRH Definition: Forcible tearing or disruption of tissue.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A process caused by injury or disease or aging and characterized by a partial/complete disruption of tissue. The disruption may be temporary or permanent and may be associated with either (1) impairment or (2) loss of function of the affected organ(s) or system(s).
CDRH Definition: A process caused by injury or disease or aging and characterized by a partial/complete disruption of tissue. The disruption may be temporary or permanent and may be associated with either (1) impairment or (2) loss of function of the affected organ(s) or system(s).

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Death of tissue due to external pressure.
CDRH Definition: Death of tissue due to external pressure.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Damage inflicted on the soft tissues and their supporting structures as the direct or indirect result of an external force, with or without disruption of structural continuity.
CDRH Definition: The report describes a non-specific injury to the skin or subcutaneous tissue. Note: Please use "Appropriate Term / Code Not Available" if the report describes a specific injury but the relevant term does not exist.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Traumatic damage and/or injury to the perineum.
CDRH Definition: Traumatic damage and/or injury to the perineum.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A fibrous band of tissue that connects normally separate body regions.
CDRH Definition: A fibrous band of tissue that connects normally separate body regions.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A state of consciousness that permits the formation of explicit and implicit memories while under general anesthesia.
CDRH Definition: A state of consciousness that permits the formation of explicit and implicit memories while under general anesthesia.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A level of stimulation delivered by a device that is greater than the intended level.
CDRH Definition: A level of stimulation that is greater than the intended level.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A brief, unintentional exposure to an electric current, which may result in local tissue damage due to thermal injury or in a cardiac dysrhythmia.
CDRH Definition: A shock caused by a brief, unintentional exposure to an electric current from a device.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Unintended electric shock from patient leads.
CDRH Definition: Unintended electric shock from patient leads. This includes an electric shock to a healthcare professional or a patient receiving a shock to an incorrect area of their body.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: The patient becomes contaminated from contact with blood/fluids on a device.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions

CDRH Definition: A hole or opening made through a membrane or other tissue or material.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A rupture in an organ(s) due to traumatic or pathologic processes.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: The complex of symptoms characterizing the disease known as radiation injury, resulting from excessive exposure (greater than 200 rads or 2 gray) of the whole body (or large part) to ionizing radiation. The earliest of these symptoms are nausea, fatigue, vomiting, and diarrhea, which may be followed by epilation, hemorrhage, inflammation of the mouth and throat, and general loss of energy. In severe cases, where the radiation exposure has been approximately 1000 Rad (10 gray) or more, death may occur within two to four weeks. Those who survive six weeks after the receipt of a single large dose of radiation to the whole body may generally be expected to recover. (U.S. Nuclear Regulatory Commission).
CDRH Definition: The complex of symptoms characterizing the disease known as radiation injury, resulting from excessive exposure of the whole body (or large part) to ionizing radiation.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Dislodgement, breakdown, or other malfunction of an artificial cardiac pacemaker, chemotherapy port, drip infusion valve, or similar implanted diagnostic or therapeutic device as a result of unconscious or habitual manipulation by the patient.
CDRH Definition: Dislodgement, breakdown, or other malfunction of an artificial cardiac pacemaker, chemotherapy port, drip infusion valve, or similar implanted diagnostic or therapeutic device as a result of unconscious or habitual manipulation by the patient.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: The removal of a previously inserted tube from a hollow organ or passageway, often from the airway.
CDRH Definition: The removal of a previously inserted tube from a hollow organ or passageway, often from the airway.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: The unintentional exposure to radiation of a person.
CDRH Definition: The unintentional exposure to radiation of a person, or a part of a persons body. This might include exposure of a healthcare professional, or the exposure of the wrong part of the body of a patient who was intended to receive therapeutic or diagnostic radiation. This includes both ionizing and non ionizing radiation.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions

CDRH Definition: A rare and potentially fatal perioperative complication of cemented bone surgery, characterised by hypotension, hypoxia, cardiac dysrhythmias, and in severe cases cardiac arrest.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions

CDRH Definition: Persistent blood flow/pressure in the aneurysm sac following an endovascular aneurysm repair (EVAR) procedure.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: An acute or chronic inflammatory process affecting the mucous membranes of any sinus cavity.
CDRH Definition: Inflammation (swelling and redness) of the paranasal sinuses, associated or related to implantation procedures or devices.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Infection local to an implanted or invasive medical device.
CDRH Definition: Infection local to an implanted or invasive medical device.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions

CDRH Definition: The accidental removal of a previously inserted line from a blood vessel.

CDRH Definition: Condition where a person experiences persistent severe and debilitating pain, involving an extremity or other body region, hyperesthesia, and localized autonomic dysfunction following injury to soft tissue or nerve

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Loss of anatomical alignment after fracture reduction.
CDRH Definition: Loss of anatomical alignment after fracture reduction.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions

CDRH Definition: Fractures around joint replacement prosthetics or implants. These can occur intraoperatively or postoperatively.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Pathological process consisting of hardening/thickening of tissue or structures at the site of an implant.
CDRH Definition: Pathological process consisting of hardening/thickening of tissue or structures.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A change in the appearance characteristics of peritoneal dialysis effluent.
CDRH Definition: A change in the appearance or other characteristics of peritoneal dialysis effluent (e.g. cloudy or discolored).

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Failure of transplanted tissue to become functional or operational, often as a result of destruction by the host's immune system.
CDRH Definition: Failure of a transplanted graft.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: Arterial blood gas test results that are outside normal limits.
CDRH Definition: Abnormal Blood Gas Measurements.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A high level of the degree to which oxygen is bound to hemoglobin given as a percentage calculated by dividing the maximum oxygen capacity into the actual oxygen content and multiplying by 100. Oxygen saturation usually is measured using pulse oximetry.
CDRH Definition: A high level of the degree to which oxygen is bound to hemoglobin given as a percentage calculated by dividing the maximum oxygen capacity into the actual oxygen content and multiplying by 100. Oxygen saturation usually is measured using pulse oximetry.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
NCIt Definition: A low level of the degree to which oxygen is bound to hemoglobin given as a percentage calculated by dividing the maximum oxygen capacity into the actual oxygen content and multiplying by 100. Oxygen saturation usually is measured using pulse oximetry.
CDRH Definition: A low level of the degree to which oxygen is bound to hemoglobin given as a percentage calculated by dividing the maximum oxygen capacity into the actual oxygen content and multiplying by 100. Oxygen saturation usually is measured using pulse oximetry.

CDRH Subset Name: Health Effects - Clinical Signs and Symptoms or Conditions
